Showers & Rainbow
Tiong Bahru, Singapore
5.50 pm, 30 September 2020

Directions

COVID-19 took the world by its ankles and lifted it off, tumbling downhill since the start of spring 2020. With the much reduced number of daily reported cases and Phase 3 in sight, Singaporeans have slowly returned to the streets of Singapore. While travelling overseas is still not an option on the table, we may contribute to the economy and support the local tourism industry that has been hit hard by the pandemic.

Here in Little India, preparations for Deepavali are underway. Hindu devotees may be found purchasing festive goods in Little India, the streets are installed with festive lightings and are ready for the festival of light. As a whole, the nation seems ready to move away from the shadow cast by COVID-19, and instead look forward to celebrating Deepavali.

During my trips to Little India in the past 2 weeks, I noticed these beautiful road signages that seem to be unique to Little India. From my research, I found that these signages can be found on several streets: Campbell Lane, Buffalo Road, Kerbau Road, Veerasamy Road, Serangoon Road and Upper Weld Road. Despite my best efforts to collect them all, I've only managed to photograph 4 of the 6 that I've listed. Locating the Serangoon Road sign left me with unglam tanned lines that shall remain on me for sometime. Perhaps in this case, rediscovering Singapore may lead you to locating this road sign that has slipped through my fingers.

SingapoRediscovers 3 Oct 2020

It's saturday fever.  Nobody in the street in early morning.  A rare and quiet scene around Chinatown. A contrast between the used to be buzzling town filled with festive moods and lifestyle comparing to the diminishing kampong village where I grew up from.

Ironically, this Sago street used to be death houses and today a temple is built here.

Covid-19 may have slowed down our lifestyle, our economy and taking away many lives.  While what were lost, there are always new opportunities, new beginnings and new discovery.

To me, Singapore rediscovers is to revisit some of my growing up fond memories places and/or find new created memories and values through every visits.

Walking down the memory street, checking out what we have been missing during those vibrant good days, refresh our childhood memories, spending more time with family, revisit Singapore and it's diverse culture and foods.  Without covid-19, we may be complacent, and always think that the other part of the pasture are greener.  It is this covid-19 that set our mindset to another new level of critical thinking, to unlearn, learn and relearn. To appreciate and be thankful that we are borned in Singapore, with the great contribution from our fore fathers especially from our founding father Mr Lee Kuan Yew.

Will Singapore continue to be a vibrant first world country? It's a test on #SGUnited.

Have always enjoyed eating chwee kueh but have not really had one that was memorable. Recently I kept seeing posts about an elderly uncle who sells chwee kueh at Taman Jurong Food Center. His chwee kuehs are very popular amongst those living around the area. Uncle actually makes the chwee kueh daily. Wanted to visit to support and also try out the famed chwee kuehs for myself. A good way to #supportlocal üòÇ note that his shop doesn't exactly have a name but the sign says Ê∞¥Á≤ø. Shop number #02-67!

Glad to say that the chwee kuehs were tasty! Enjoyed the smooth texture of the rice cakes that had a delicate chewy texture. The chye poh were for me both savoury yet sweet and surprisingly they were not too oily. Think the chilli which was on the sweeter side also went well with the kuehs. In all, it isn't something that will blow your mind but you can definitely taste the difference in quality as compared to other chwee kuehs. The contrasting savoury and sweetness in the chye poh gives it an edge over other versions too. 

Uncle manages the store by himself so waiting time could get long but it's worth the wait! His shop closes at 1.30pm daily so have to go early!

Waking up here in a weekday ain‚Äôt that bad, especially when I get to edit photos all day - which can be really therapeutic! 

I know of people who absolutely abhor the process of photo editing but truly love the act of shooting. Over the years, I‚Äôve gravitated to enjoying the former more.

These days, I carve out time on a Friday/weekend night to edit photos and this has become some sort of a meditative process for me after a tiring week at work. Beyond this, I typically select a playlist on YouTube/Spotify that I currently feel like zoning out to, make a cup of tea, get comfortable and let the magic happen.‚ú®

Had an awesome morning at @nestopia_sg at @sentosa_island today! The girls had a ball of a time climbing nets, crossing bridges and sliding down slides (one's pretty fast and steep, they say!). Being outdoors at 10am was rather hot though, especially with face masks on üòÖ But they lasted for the hour we were booked for!
.
Honestly, I wasn't sure I'd visit Nestopia when I first heard about it as you have to pay entrance fees ($9-10/hr) - Singapore has loads of free outdoor playgrounds after all üòÜ. We decided to visit after redeeming the free NDP Sentosa tokens (go redeem yours if you haven't!) which covered entry for two kids (one adult can enter free with a kid). When we got there, I was pretty impressed by the playground structure. It looked about two stories high which made it really exciting for the kids. And there‚Äôs something about playing at a playground with the beach in the background - felt like we were on holiday somewhere! The kids enjoyed themselves so much they wanted to return another time - I said okay, if there is promo on the entrance fees üòã
.
It wasn't crowded the Tuesday school holiday morning we were there with only around 8 kids. Apparently late afternoon weekends are pretty popular though. There's a capacity limit of 15 kids now, so do call ahead to book a slot if you're planning to visit üòä
.
Are you enjoying your Sep holiday so far? üòâ

„ÄêAng Mo Kio #3 - Fried Rice„Äë
Where do you get your fried-rice-fix? Where is your favourite _zhichar_ or western food stall? If you are craving for some old school western food and fried rice, you have to visit Yummy Western stall located at Blk 409 Ang Mo Kio Avenue 10 (avoid peak hours if you are in a hurry). The chef cooking this fried rice has been in the business for about 20 years - no wonder the fried rice tastes so good and full of ‚Äòwok hei‚Äô flavour! Truly satisfying!

This week, #dabaogram tried a new dimension of food plating with a floral touch. Greens like cucumbers and parsley were added to give it a refreshing look and feel . We reshaped the side dishes and positioned them like an arrow pointing upwards. Can you see it?  Finally, we used some of the accompanying chilli sauce to add some vibrant colour to the dish. Viola!

We would like to thank Yummy Western for preparing such delicious fried rice and western food. According to the owner, all dishes were marinated using a  special curated sauce. This is an un-sponsored series in which we hope to raise awareness of our rich local hawker food culture and help local hawkers during this unprecedented period. Join us on this journey of rediscovery where we dabao and transform our local favourites into works of gastronomic art, one district at a time. Tag us in your post if you would try your own ‚Äòdabaogram‚Äô at home. 

Next week‚Äôs makeover dish is our favourite for Ang Mo Kio. Stay tuned cos‚Äô you won‚Äôt want to miss it, see ya!

We also love to meet up with my parents, sisters and nieces in their home or in a park for lantern walk. Very honoured to be part of @NeverBeforeSG; Singapore's first and largest online art showcase  presented by National Museum of Singapore @natmuseum_sg and curated by Yang Derong @derongisyang. 

Arranged in nine chapters about our take on #Covid19, it showcases 140 works by 91 Singapore based creatives who consist of photographers, videographers, writers, artists, architects and designers.

These are the images I captured during and after the ‚ÄúCircuit Breaker‚Äù. Most of the photos are primarily blue in colour, reflecting the blue mood: lots of uncertainty and a feeling of loneliness.

Blue, however, is also the colour of the sea and sky, which I was able to spend more time admiring and learning to appreciate nature more.

#NeverBeforeSG

Life was not meant to be lived in black and white.

On 1 October 2020, we celebrated Mid-Autumn Festival or ‰∏≠ÁßãËäÇ (also known as Mooncake Festival) at the Singapore Embassy in Ankara with a small group of Turkish #FriendsofSingapore (due to social distancing requirements). We enjoyed a variety of delicious mooncakes and Chinese tea, and learnt about the history and mythology behind the festival!
.
As a multiracial and multireligious country, Singapore celebrates a wide range of festivals ‚Äì both religious and traditional, giving our society a vibrant mosaic of sights, sounds, tastes and beliefs! The Mid-Autumn Festival is celebrated by the Singaporean Chinese and is one of the oldest festivals dating back to 1600 BC. This marks the start of the harvest season and a time of year that the moon is at its brightest! 
.
Here is a short video of the celebration at the Embassy!

Uncle Sng was very friendly and it was a good long chat with Saiful too, which shared the vantage point to shoot his house like a drone without a drone üò¨

Believe it or not, it was my first time coming here, and I think next time I would sit for a kopi and pisang goreng. Anyone wants to join?

All pictures from #Pixel3 cos I brought #NikonZ6 with big fat lens and yet forgot to put the XQD card inside, and yes no one else shoots that that card. üòÖ

PS. If you go there for some shots, please be respectful. The aunty at the yellow house is quite old and she needs her nap in the afternoon, please be quiet. Keep in mind you are in private property although there is no fence for some of the houses. This is not a zoo and these people are not a display for your camera. This is their home, their life. If you have a few minutes to say hi and chat, you will leave with a lot of stories like I did today.

post_caption:
Most don't think much of a simple Tutu Kueh - little steamed rice-flour cakes filled with single fillings such as peanut, coconut and occasionally chocolate, served over pieces of pandan leafs. As Singapore's hawker culture slowly declines, these little gems are nowadays hard to come by. You find them at traditional shops but rarely are they freshly prepared. 

As a part of Singapore's unique food culture and identity, shops such as Tan's Tutu Kueh are doing their best to keep the hawker culture alive. Known as the OG of Tutu kueh, the family business has been delighting locals with their freshly steamed kuehs since mid 1900s. 

Really enjoy their chocolate and coconut filled Tutu Kuehs and it has become ny go to place for good Tutu Kueh. Heck, I wouldn't even bother trying Tutu Kueh from any other places, they just don't come close. 

Hope that everyone gets to try their famous Tutu Kuehs! They have 2 outlets, located at Havelock Rd and Clementi. Note the timings are different so do check them out before heading down ‚ò∫Ô∏è

Mini Bath Tubs
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

According to local geologists, the exact source of the spring remains unknown, but it is believed that its origin may be southwest of its actual location, possibly at Bukit Timah. Hot springs are formed when underground water comes into contact with hot rock masses. The resulting high pressure causes the water to seep upwards through cracks, forcing itself out of the ground as a spring.

A series of tests conducted by the PSB Corporation and SGS Testing & Control Services found the spring water contains 420 mg of chloride per litre, an amount which is substantially higher than the 35 to 100 mg in the water from Choa Chu Kang & Bedok waterworks. It was also found that the sulphide content is three times more than tap water & the spring water is also slightly alkaline due to the presence of minerals. Natural spring waters may have health benefits, similar to the hot springs of other countries near tectonic plates with volcanoes, in a search for cures for some skin conditions, as well as debilitating ailments like rheumatism & arthritis. Although local rheumatologists conceded that hydrotherapy is an accepted treatment that can be helpful for mild forms of rheumatism or muscle strain, they, along with dermatologists, remain skeptical of claims about the alternative healing of the natural spring water.

Hot hard water bubbles continuously in the well, releasing a slightly unpleasant sulphur mud-like odour together with steam. The temperature of the spring water is measured by precision instrument to be constant 70 ¬∞C (160 ¬∞F). In an investigation carried out by the Nanyang Technological University in 1994, the hot spring was found to have an estimated yield of approximately 150 litres (33 imp gal; 40 US gal) per minute at ground level through installed steel casings.

Colors, colors, colors everywhere! It was indeed a pleasant experience walking through the colorful Little India. I personally have not explored much of Little India and this SingapoRediscovers Photo Contest has just made me uncover another side of Singapore. 

Of particular interest is the house of Tan Teng Niah -a vividly colorful Chinese villa located just a few minutes‚Äô walk from Little India Mrt station. This house belonged to a Chinese businessman with the same name in the 1900s and is one of the last surviving old merchant houses that survived Singapore‚Äôs rapidly evolving urban development plans. Colors of the rainbow (blue, green, yellow, orange, pink etc) adorn the exterior facet of the building and it is now preserved under landmark status from the National Heritage Board. I could just spend the whole day there admiring this beautiful structure.

Of course, other than the house of Tan Teng Niah, there are many colorful mural painting and street art found all over Little India and I think I will be back soon to explore more of these‚Ä¶.

1) went to explore a part of SG that used to only have a 10m or so back alley of Haji Lane, now with more street art to boost its vibrant funkyness

Nice to see art incorporated among air-con compressors, electrical boxes, motorcycles and flying wild pigeons 

2) noticed an unprecedented number of people wearing red and masks with SG logos on it, somehow can really feel the pride of those wearers this year ‚ú®

3) Also visited an ex-colleague friend from üáµüá≠ who's gonna give birth and has to leave SG.

Grateful to have worked at a backpacker hostel before the pandemic, getting to know hardworking Filipinos, the challenges they face and who contribute a lot to SG economy, as well as many Nigerian guests who may intimidate people with their body-build, but are generally polite well mannered with sense of humour

‚ÄúCantonese mooncakes are most commonly seen in Singapore. The golden brown pastry is filled with lotus paste and an optional salted duck egg, glazed with egg yolks before baking. Apart from lotus paste, the less common red date paste is also used as Cantonese mooncake filling. The red date paste gives it a dark red tone with slight fruity and citrus taste.

[ Who Painted The Tree? ]

I have visited Katong Park and walked pass this tree more than times than I could count but I have never realised the beauty of it until recently someone told me that there is a "Rainbowüåà" tree in this park.

As I walked and looked closer, the tree does look like someone painted it, but it is actually naturally gorgeous. From the #NParks signboard I learned that this colourful tree that features rainbow coloured streaks along its trunk is called Rainbow Eucalyptus. As the tree sheds its outer bark at different times to reveal the neon green bark underneath, over time, this layer is exposed to air and ages into different colors ‚Äî from green to blue to purple to orange to maroon before finally falling off the tree.

This colourful tree is also the only one of its kind in Singapore and has been listed by the National Parks as a Heritage Tree. If you are the type that like to chase after rainbows,¬†it is located at Katong Park, near the Fort Road exit of East Coast Park.

p.s. No tree was harmed in the making of this series

Chinatown‚Å†
‚Å†
Long before the arrival of Raffles in 1819, a small immigrant Chinese population had already settled in Singapore, cultivating gambier and pepper. When Singapore‚Äôs free port was established, more Chinese and other immigrants flocked to its shores. For easy administration, Raffles grouped various immigrant communities into ethnic quarters. In his 4 November 1822 letter to the Town Committee the area from the ‚ÄúBoat Quay southwest bank of the Singapore River‚Äù was designated a Chinese Kampong. This self-contained kampong or community settlement became the home of many Chinese immigrants, and a transit point for coolies (unskilled labourers) going to Malaya. That kampong and Chinese centre grew, eventually becoming Chinatown.‚Å†
‚Å†
The original kampong was divided into zones, a sector for each Chinese community of the same provincial origin and dialect group.‚Å†
‚Å†
Different trades were confined to specific areas, so each street took on its own identity. From delicacies to death-houses, there were businessmen, traders, craftsmen, hawkers and peddlers to provide all of the peoples‚Äô needs. ‚Å†
‚Å†
Chinatown has become Singapore‚Äôs largest Historic District. Its four sub-districts ‚Äì Bukit Pasoh, Kreta Ayer, Telok Ayer and Tanjong Pagar ‚Äì were given conservation status in the late 1980s. Much of the town has changed, but fortunately, remnants of its colourful past are still present and old traditions have endured. During festivals such as the Lunar New Year, and the Mid-autumn Festival, there are celebrations and festive shopping. Always dressed for the occasion, Chinatown would be colourful, lit up and abuzz with activity, attracting not just the Chinese but other locals as well as tourists.‚Å†
‚Å†.‚Å†
Source: eresources.nlb.gov.sg‚Å†

Sago Street

Did you know the street received its name because there were numerous sago factories in that area during the 1840s. In the late 19th century, this area became well known for its number of prostitute dens.

Fast forward to the more recent history, this street were occupied by mostly wet and dry markets as well as hawkers. Currently this street is known mainly as a tourist attraction that sell a range of souvenirs and street food, also for the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple which is located along the street.

I did enjoy rediscovering Singapore and finding these hidden photography spots while also trying out street photography which I must admit that I‚Äôm totally bad at it.

Kampong Glam is one of my go-to hangout spots but today‚Äôs visit was made even more meaningful through the #SingapoRediscovers campaign. At one of Singapore‚Äôs surviving street side barber, I waited in queue to get a shave. Mr Chen, unperturbed by onlookers, continued executing his craft like a hyper focused surgeon even as I hastily took a few snapshots. 
When it was my turn, Mr Chen introduced himself and swiftly finished the shave. We did not get to talk much though, as Mr Chen bantered with his friend who arrived shortly during my shave. In that moment, it felt like I returned to the 1990‚Äôs. 

Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. It‚Äôs an opportunity to re-live our nation‚Äôs history while tuning into modern narratives of ‚Äúhidden‚Äù spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

The old #shophouses in Singapore are an important part of our heritage and they are a delight to photograph. Along Duxton road, you can find rows of two- and three-storey shophouse units that are beautifully-restored.

One great example is the former Six Senses Duxton, a boutique hotel that took up eight restored shophouses. Sadly, they have ceased operations not long ago.

#FunFact: Duxton Road had a seedy reputation for its opium dens, gambling dens & brothels during the early 19th and 20th centuries!

Check out our blog #linkinbio for more fun facts & secret insights about Singapore >> www.monsterdaytours.com/travel-tips-and-guides

The best thing about cable car rides at @sentosa_island has got to be the stunning views you get to see üíï Throwback to last weekend's trip to Sentosa when we got the Mastercard 1-for-1 fun pass promo. Other than ten minute each on the Mega Bounce at Mega Adventure for the girls, the fun passes got our whole family on round trips on the Faber and Sentosa cable car lines.
.
The cable car ride is quite a novelty even for us adults and I must say we all so love the views on both lines (an empty Adventure Cove was a little sad to see tho üòî). The younger one was a bit nervous initially üòÖ but at the end of the rides they were rather bummed that we couldn't go again.
.
Without the promo, I doubt we would have thought of going for cable car rides. But with the promo it came up to $40 for the four of us - pretty good deal if you ask me üòÑ
.
Weekend's coming! Have you made plans for it? üòä

Clara Simanjuntak is Nyananyana Eco-fashion founder and designer. The clothing and accessories brand was conceptualised in Singapore in 2011. After a long journey of sourcing and research about all natural fabrics and dyes from plants, the brand finally launched in 2017 in Jakarta. Nyananyana is currently based in Singapore.‚Å£‚Å£

üè°The Residence of Tan Teng Niah
.
A brightly colored landmark that stands along the arts belt in Little India. It is the last remaining Chinese villa in the history of Little India, Singapore.
Tan Teng Niah, a successful businessman who owned a confectionary business and various other smaller businesses, built the villa in 1900 for his wife. The Residence of Tan Teng Niah won the Singapore Institute of Architects Honourable Mention Award in 1991.
Was it always this colourful? The Residence of Tan Teng Niah villa was originally whitewashed. The colors were added fairly recently.
Found along Kerbau Road, it is probably one of the most photographed buildings in Little India.
.

You want to get started with night photography but not to spend that long 4 hours. 

I get it !

So I came up with a 2 hours workshop

What we‚Äôll do... 

I‚Äôll coach you the basic elements of night photography, providing you with tips and techniques of low light and long exposure photography. 

We will be working on camera settings to create different effects to capture fascinating images as the day changes from twilight hour into the night. 

What you‚Äôll get...

At the end of the workshop, you will acquire the knowledge to capture light trails, to create the effect of light burst and silky waters, creating stunning colour tones to your night images as well as capturing modern and historical architecture illuminated with colourful lights that adorned the cityscape.

No filter required!

Just practical stuff from your in-camera settings.

Where we‚Äôll be...

This workshop takes place at one of Singapore's most vibrant quays along the Singapore River, within a vicinity that is surrounded by historical and modern architecture. 

The location provides you with all the required subjects of interest to photograph in low light and to acquire the skills of night photography.

What others said....

Don‚Äôt just hear this from me. 

Swipe to your left to read what participant has to say about this workshop.

All that for $120 per person.

And that‚Äôs not the end of us...

I keep the communication channel open for all my workshops‚Äô past and present participants. 

Participants still text or email me from time to time, checking in on unclear camera setups, asking for opinions and reviews of their work. 

Book your spot through info@carolinepang.com

As life slowly returns to a new normal with a focus on rediscovering our local sights and sounds, the family decided to embark on our #FirstWonder in the new normal at @singaporemarriott during this weekend for a well-deserved break from our usual routine of studying and working at home.

During our staycation, the family felt safe and assured that the hotel staff were doing their best to maintain the highest level of cleanliness and safety for guests. It was a home away from home where we were pampered by the hotel staff with lots of delicious memories and laughter.

We were greeted by ‚ÄúApricot Grove‚Äù featuring pink apricot flowers where the soft pink background makes for a welcoming entrance. Don‚Äôt forget to look up for the Colonnade of Lights  showcasing 1,500 beautiful paper lanterns painted by people from various walks of life. The kaleidoscope of colours from Illuminations of Joy was so mesmerising and the concept is inspired by traditional cellophane lanterns. Don‚Äôt miss the cute Prosperity Rats which are at the far end near Floral Fantasy! GBTB Mid-Autumn display is from now till 4 Oct. Are you planning to go too?

While my wife had lunch with her friend, I took a chance to try something I've only heard about, Salted and Hung. I went for the "Feed Me" d√©gustation menu to have an understanding of Salted and Hung's repertoire. Set aside just under S$200, and be prepared for a culinary ride through Australia, with a dash of Southeast Asia familiarities. 

The range felt playful to me, especially how the very opening bite was an Ebi Panna Cotta... Who the heck starts with dessert? So what's familiar is turned upside down, with this dessert being savoury to the palate. The IPA Sourdough was divine, esp when paired with whipped lard WITH a generous drop of chili oil (you have to try to understand how it plays with you mind!). The other butter was seaweed based, and it was yummy, giving the crunchy bread flavours of the sea. 

Chef Drew and his professional crew did everything so intently, you sense the purpose of the ingredients coming together. More often than not, contemporay fusion food can be a turn off when it's in the chef's mind, but the execution just doesn't mindmeld it to the diner. These guys just did a Spock on me, and I'm pretty damn sure you'll get it too once you give it a go! üßê

Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

Kampong ‚Äì a term to describe traditional villages or urban slum areas in towns and cities. 

In the early days, there used to be many kampongs scattered all over Singapore. However, with development and urbanization, these kampongs have been replaced with modern skyscrapers.

As an urban kid, kampong lifestyle is something that I find it hard to visualize and the only references I have of it are from my grandparents‚Äô narration of their happy childhood days back in the kampong era.

Upon knowing that there is still the last kampong in Singapore (Kampong Lorong Buangkok), I jumped at the chance to explore it. It was a strange feeling walking through the kampong. Despite being surrounded by the all-so-familiar modern architectures and bustling roads, time seemed to come to a standstill here. Low-rise single-storey houses made of wood with zinc roofs instead of high-rise apartments; lush greeneries instead of dense man-made structures; a peaceful and quiet surrounding instead of the hustle and bustle of the city, this is indeed a whole new world to me!

I took my time to explore and admire the place, soaking up the atmosphere of this lovely location (and at the same time trying very hard to ignore the constant attacks from the bloodsucking mosquito..). This visit has definitely changed my impression of Singapore ‚Äì there is more to Singapore than meets the eye!!

<309> ‚ÄúA Paradoxically Intriguing Temple‚Äù

Don‚Äôt you find it paradoxical to see an ancient-looking 100-year-old Chinese temple surrounded by modern, high-rise buildings and located in a street named after Mohamed Sultan? That‚Äôs so uniquely Singapore! 

The three big red Chinese characters on the walls of the temple are read ‚ÄúÈ≥≥Â±±ÂØ∫‚Äú (FeÃÄng shaÃÑnsiÃÄ in Mandarin or Hong San See in Hokkien), which can be literally translated as ‚ÄúTemple on Phoenix Hill‚Äù.

A Phoenix is a mystical bird that rises from the ashes. Coincidentally, the temple was restored to its glory ten years ago and had since gone on to win an Award of Excellence in the 2010 UNESCO Asia-Pacific Heritage Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation. Isn‚Äôt the name befitting?

What‚Äôs more, the temple worships the God of Fortune. I would have climbed up those steep steps without hesitation if I had known that earlier. Times are bad, every prayer counts. 

William

Remark: I was later informed by someone in my IG that the temple‚Äôs main deity is not the God of Fortune. Alas! There goes my glimmer of hope that a prayer at this temple may bring me some fortune. (laughs).

Among them are Tanah Merah I and Tanah Merah II, bungalows¬†built in the 1880s to accommodate the British Officers of the Royal Artillery, Coastal Defence Command based on Sentosa Island.¬†Known as the Officers'¬†Mess, it was where the officers and their families ate and relaxed by dancing and playing tennis.¬†‚Å£

Discovered this majestic instagram-worthy #wallmural (Titled¬†Medley Alley) with @photographyholic at one of the small side laneways of lively Katong. According to what I read online, this eclectic mural that united the two walls in #MedleyAlley form wings made¬†of colourful Peranakan tiles, and the wall art represent the metamorphosis between generations.¬†

Also found out that this piece of art was one of the many that were painted for the #KatongJooChiatArtCircuit, in hope to revitalise Katong and JooChiat area. Next time when you are around the area, try and see if you are able to find them for pictures and #ootd.

‚ÄúOne thing I really love about Little India is its rich culture and history that also live within unassuming hotel buildings.
 
Many of the smaller hotels in Little India such as The Daulat and Perak Hotel started off as shophouses, and what‚Äôs not known to many is that Hotel 81 Rochor was first built just before the Second World War. The Great Madras also takes up a building that has been proudly perched on Madras Street since the 1940s.‚Äù
 
Captured by @darrensohphoto as part of #SingapoRediscovers ‚Äì capture your own hidden gem in Little India and hashtag us too!

post_caption:
SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Sago Lane / Sago Street, in Chinatown

Sago Lane (and Sago Street) gets its name from the many sago factories in the area in mid-1800s Singapore. However, Sago Lane is more famous (or infamous) for another reason - its death houses.

In the past¬†when most Chinese immigrants lived in Chinatown area, the terminally ill would go to a death house where they literally awaited their fate ‚Äì death.

Now the street has just been revitalised with new arch Chinatown signs and Chinese orientated shelters. 

Of course the main attraction is still the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple. Even if you are not there to pray, the lanterns or lighting (during some festive periods) are an attraction itself.

Given the most depressing covid period, any nice temple or street lighting certainly cheers us up and gives us hope. üôè

Happy Mid-Autumn Festival! üåï‚ú® #SeteMilKmEmSingapura ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
One of my favourite things about living in Singapore is celebrating cultural festivals that weren't on our radar before moving to Asia. Today we're celebrating the Mid-Autumn or Moon Festival, which has a history dating back 3000 years! ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Traditionally it was a time to thank the gods at the end of the autumn harvest, and the festival is celebrated every year on the 15th day of the 8th lunar calendar month. This marks the day the Chinese believed the moon was at its brightest and fullest size, so we're spending the evening looking up to test this theory üòÇ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Paper lanterns in every shape and size can be found decorating many spots in the city, and even though the festival was scaled back this year because of the pandemic, @gardensbythebay still went all out!üèÆ‚†Ä
‚†Ä

Well, now till end August there's a 55% off for the attractions at Canopy Park and that finally got us there üòÜ
.
Some of the attraction tickets, including our Walking Net tics, include Canopy Park entrance fees and essentially we paid slightly over $20 for our family of four. I had thought my girls would be fine with the Walking Net given that they were fearless at Airzone (the net playgound at City Square Mall), but they were rather spooked by the height (you can see all the way down to the mall) and they said a lot harder to walk on compared to Airzone. I quite agree with them; we were all drenched in sweat by the time we made our way to the end of the net. But that said, we got the hang of it - the trick is to side step - and soon we all found the net to be quite enjoyable to walk around and sit on üòÜ
.
It wasn't very crowded when we were there on Saturday morning - only a little crowded with children at the Foggy Bowls. We were expecting more people given that Jewel just started a promo where you can redeem Canopy Park entry for 2 pax with one receipt of any amount spent at Jewel (1st 500 redemptions). The girls had a field day at the Discovery Slides (only 2 slides out of 4 operating btw) and they didn't even have to queue despite a capacity limit of 5 at any one time at Discovery Slides.
.
We're thinking of the Bouncing Nets (bookings for these seem to have sold out fast!) and Canopy Bridge next. Anyone know if these two attractions are good? üòä
.

‚ÄúEver seen a mooncake as large as this? Originating from the largest dialect group in Singapore, the Hokkien mooncake is also known as the Scholar Cake, distributed to those who sat for the Imperial examinations in ancient China.

Each Hokkien mooncake is made of candied winter melon, tangerine peel, melon and sesame seeds, sugar, and lard. I chose the Hokkien mooncake from the 89-year-old Tan Hock Seng Shop at Telok Ayer and was greeted by a warm and cheery old lady. She asked if I was getting it for my grandparents as youngsters these days generally do not know these old-school traditional confectioneries.

As a Hokkien-lang, I still remember my grandmother giving me a slice (because it‚Äôs really much bigger than the usual mooncakes) when I was young during Mid-Autumn Festival. This brings back lots of childhood memories, including old-school, heritage playgrounds such as the one shaped like a watermelon in Tampines. Traditions will be lost forever if we do not continue to preserve it and upkeep them.‚Äú

Captured by @stormscape for #SingapoRediscovers. Comment below and share with us your childhood Mid-Autumn memories.

Stones Stacking
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

In 1998, the Ministry of Defence (Mindef) acquired the land containing the spring for the expansion of the nearby Sembawang Air Base, leaving F&N with less than 4 hectares (10 acres) of land. Its water-bottling plant survived until the early 1990s however. In January 2002, locals' interest to the hot spring, which had caught the attention of Singaporeans after the surrounding land had been cleared to begin the RSAF air base extension. Sembawang community leaders gathered signatures to petition Mindef, which was going to fence off the area, to preserve & develop the hot spring for the general public. Mindef gave the green light to the appeals & opened a small side gate pavement for the public to access the spring.

During that same year, a series of scalding cases, including an incident in which a senior citizen diabetic lost six toes to gangrene after soaking in the hot spring, prompted the Singapore General Hospital to warn that people with nerve disorders or diseases affecting blood circulation should be cautious to hot mineral springs. As a result of some negative rumors and hearsay, and the RSAF redevelopment, public interest began to wane & the number of visitors dwindled.

Escape the City, Experience the Nature.

Exploring Singapore from a different perspective.

Sajeev Digital Studio is more than a photography studio. Taken by Mr K Sajeev Lal, these photographs perform an important social function: they help South Asian male migrant workers find love back home in India and Sri Lanka! Mr Sajeev happily claims that he has a success rate of 100% üòâ
.
An affable and jovial soul, Mr Sajeev gave me a tour of his studio and shared his personal story. I learned that he taught himself photography on a Yashica film camera when he was 15. He learnt film developing later, and adroitly turned his passion into a profession. I‚Äôm also glad that Mr Sajeev was game enough to pose for my photographs. As a photographer, I know that willing subjects are hard to come by. Mr Sajeev‚Äôs willingness made the photo-taking experience so much more fun and imbued deeper meaning into these photographs that you see here.
.
One more thing that stood out for me was the thousands of portraits of migrant workers the adorned the walls of the little studio. These portraits formed an eclectic mosaic of untold stories. I took a moment to appreciate the fact that much of Singapore‚Äôs modern development would have been impossible without them, and that they too have suffered greatly because of the coronavirus. Looking at these portraits turned out to be a gentle reminder that we can do more to appreciate our migrant workers in our midst. I realised that rediscovering Singapore is not just about visiting local places of interest because we can‚Äôt go overseas ‚Äì it‚Äôs about rediscovering the different threads that form our magnificent social fabric, and how it is up to each and every one of us to make it stronger.
.

Of Murals and We-fies

The Gelam Gallery rejuvenates the back alleys of Kampong Gelam, where glamorous pictures are taken against the backdrop of paintings, bright and colourful. These murals bring new life to the historical site, engaging the new generation with the past. New memories of this place are created, tying generations of Singaporeans together.

While Kampong Gelam used to be the enclave for the Malay community in Singapore, and in the present where much of the district's flavour revolves around the Malay heritage still, places like the Gelam Gallery act as an avenue to attract the nation to visit Kampong Gelam and learn about its history and the Malay culture. By giving it a fresh paint of life, it ensures continuity in the knowledge of its history.

22 on 22. Did you know that this large halo that appeared around the sun and seen by many in Singapore at around noon today (22 Sep) is what scientists call a ‚Äú22-degree halo‚Äù? (Because the ring has a radius of approximately 22 degrees around the sun.) So yup, 22 on 22üëΩ
.
What causes this phenomenon? Millions of tiny ice crystals in cirrus clouds that refract and reflect light in just the right orientation and position with respect to your eye for the halo to be visible.
.
Stay safe, and look up, people. You won‚Äôt find rainbows on the ground.
.

This is Sajeev. He is the owner of Sajeev Digital Studio in Little India, a cramped but friendly space where the walls are lined with thousands of past portraits he‚Äôs taken over the years.

His main clientele consists of foreign workers from India and Sri Lanka who send their portraits back home so their families can help in the matchmaking process and search for their future wives. He says his business has been affected by Covid as new foreign workers have stopped entering the country. Still, he was gracious enough to give me a quick tour of his studio, observe a shoot, and discuss a bit of his unique story and business model.

Scenes from Sago Street

Singapore‚Äôs Chinatown precinct has been one of my favorite places to photograph since moving to this country about 18 months ago. It‚Äôs a bustling area where new and old traditions blend together, and there‚Äôs always something interesting to point the camera at. It‚Äôs a place full of life, but starting around the 1920s, Chinatown‚Äôs Sago Street and Sago Lane were also a place full of death.

In that time, the area was home to many lower class Chinese immigrants. Superstition dictated that it was bad luck to die within one‚Äôs own home, and proper funerals were costly. Out of that sad reality came a pragmatic solution: death houses. For a small fee, the sick and elderly could live out their remaining days on the second floor of a death house. The first floor was reserved for funeral services.

Due to the poor conditions in death houses, the practice was eventually banned in 1961. Nowadays, all traces of the death houses have vanished, and the area between Sago Street and Sago Lane is the site of the well-known Buddha Tooth Relic Temple.

post_caption:
[Kovan/Buangkok Precinct] Last Kampong in Singapore and amongst us

Rediscovery is about exploration and searching for new perspective to present it.

Do you know we still have kampong in Singapore?¬†

Do you know that the last kampong is right next to our public housing estate?

We have come a long way for housing in Singapore. It is great to rediscover the old kampong days of Singapore face to face. You can get to see those old road signage with 4 digit postal code ( Photo 1). It is amazing to find a real kampong amongst the green (photo2) It also  always surprised me that it is right next to our public housing estate ( Photo 3) . It is worth a visit before it is gone.

New Featured Merchant: Darshini's Beauty

Relish in the ultimate beauty experience at Darshini Beauty & Spa, where you'll feel beautiful inside and out. Their professional beauticians come with years of experience from India, so you can truly enjoy their stunning array of beauty services, available for any occasion.

They offer a vast range of services, including eyebrow threading, henna, hair treatments, waxing, skin care, and more. Their Henna Art is one of their distinctive treatments. Rediscovering Joo Chiat/Katong and Kampong Gelam

üìçJoo Chiat / Katong
‚Ä¢Former Queen's Theatre - one of the main entertainment places in Geylang from 1930 to 1982
‚Ä¢Mindanao Gum Heritage Tree (Rainbow Tree) - has distinctive peeling bark with multi-coloured streaks. Why are there so many colours? This is because the patches of outer bark are shed at different times, showing the bright-green inner bark which matures to give blue, purple, orange and then maroon tones.
‚Ä¢Archeological Dig for Fort Tanjong Katong - remnants of Fort Tanjong Katong which stood from 1879 to 1901, was one of the oldest military forts built by the former British colonial  government of Singapore

üìçKampong Gelam
‚Ä¢Masjid Sultan (Golden Mosque)- focal point for Singapore‚Äôs Muslim community. The onion-shaped dome base is decorated with glass bottle ends, donated by lower-income Muslims during its construction so that all Muslims, not just the rich, could contribute.
‚Ä¢Streetside Barber - the last of Singapore's streetside barber shop ($6.00 only! open everyday except Wed and Sun)

Isn't it amazing that there's a piece of history in almost all corners of Singapore? Behind the industrialization and development the country is going through, may the memories of yesteryears be kept alive for the next generations to see.

Buddha Relic Tooth Temple

"Rediscover and appreciating one of the hidden beauty and gem of Singapore. Such a beautiful and magnificent structure"

This Tang-styled Chinese Buddhist temple is located in the historic district of Chinatown, Singapore. It has richly designed interiors and comprehensive exhibits on Buddhist art and history which tell stories of culture over thousands of years old. The building‚Äôs design was inspired by the Buddhist Mandala, a symbol of Buddhist culture that represents the universe.

Singapore as we all know is a place rich in culture with people still embracing the principles and beliefs passed to them through generations. Prayer is an integral part of the their culture - regardless of what religion you are in. Temples are found all over Singapore and their distinct beauty shines through despite being surrounded by modern buildings. It is a place of worship and where people spend time with their loved ones such as offering incense and attend meditations. Visiting these temples will help you to understand and experience the culture and beliefs of the people In Singapore.

As part of the SingapoRediscovers campaign, I visited Katong Park. The park was constructed on the site of the Tanjong Katong Fort (1879-1901), the only "true fort" in Singapore reflecting the 19th century military architecture. 

A Heritage Tree, the Mindanao Gum (Eucalyptus deglupta) or rainbow eucalyptus is also found here. It is unique because it is the only eucalyptus to live in the rainforest and has a multi-colored bark. Patches of outer bark are shed at different times, showing the bright-green inner bark which matures to give blue, purple, orange and then maroon tones. 

Due to the travel restrictions, I have spent a lot of time exploring hidden gems in Singapore and this was definitely one of them! It's amazing how much heritage and culture can be found in our neighbourhood if we take the time to explore. Rediscover Singapore today!

Appreciating the hidden gems of Little India, Joo Chiat and Chinatown 

üìçLittle India
‚Ä¢Little India - Once a place for racecourse, cattle herders and brick kilns. Now one of Singapore‚Äôs most vibrant districts.
‚Ä¢Little India Street Art / Five Foot Way -Explore Little India's rich multicultural history through its vibrant walls. ‚òùüèΩOn a side note, did you notice that 5-foot-way? the roofed continuous walkway commonly found in front of shops, the name refers to the width of the passageway. These walkways were meant to protect pedestrians from the hot tropical sun as well as rain.
‚Ä¢Deepavali Street Light Up - One of the major cultural festivals in Singapore, Deepavali (also known as ‚ÄúDiwali‚Äù or the ‚ÄúFestival of Lights‚Äù) is a celebration that marks the triumph of good over evil. 
‚Ä¢House of Tan Teng Niah - windows of the unique and colorful Chinese Villa that was built in 1900

üìçKampong Gelam
‚Ä¢Streetside Barbershop
‚Ä¢Spiral Staircases of Bugis - These external pre-cast concrete staircases first made their appearance at the rear of shophouses from the mid-1920s. Their introduction facilitated an important regular routine for households and residents living in the shophouses ‚Äì the collection of night-soil. Night-soil is a euphemism for human faeces. The term came about, as human waste was collected in buckets in the silence of the night and sometimes, soil was used as a cover. A night-soil carrier would enter the alleys behind the shophouses and climb these spiral staircases to each storey. That was where buckets filled with night-soil were placed.

„ÄêSeng Kang #1 ‚Äì Char Siew Noodle„Äë
Situated at the North-Eastern part of Singapore, Sengkang was once occupied by fishing villages, rubber and pepper plantations. During the mid-20th century, this area was known as ‚ÄúKangkar‚Äù which literally means ‚ÄúFoot of Harbour‚Äù.

Although with younger generations residing at this district, the love of local hawker food remains identical to any other part of Singapore. Seng Kang has a wide array of hawker fare and even had their very first vending machines caf√© for all the dabao-food lovers.

To kick-start our feature on Seng Kang, we picked a traditional staple menu in most hawker centres ‚Äì Char Siew Noodle.
 
A perfect serving of Char Siew Noodle contains egg noodles cooked al dente, tossed in flavoured sauce and topped with slices of yummy, slightly charred roast pork and leafy vegetables. Simple but satisfying!

Where is your favourite Char Siew Noodle stall? Comment below to tell us where to find this traditional dish. Stay tuned for our post when we reveal the stall name and learn about our behind-the-scenes process. See ya.

I was strolling around Sago Lane and its surrounding area a week back. It used to be the home for several funeral parlours or death houses. As I walk on the Sago Lane closer to the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, a gust of wind blew strongly, shaking the red lanterns hung around the temple. It felt a bit spooky, but it also brought in a sense of amazement in me.

Continuing after, I went to the adjacent side of Sago Lane, called Sago Street. It was named that way because during the 1800s, there were many sago factories there. I also learned that it used to house a number of brothels around the late 19th century.¬†

I explored into some alleyways in wonder and in one moment, I realized that I got to pick up my camera and shoot.

When we are able to go back traveling again to Singapore, go visit Chinatown! It is an amazing precinct rich with history :)

<332> ‚ÄúA Fishing Platform Inside A Park!‚Äù

Look at all those wooden planks, massive nets and house-like structure above the water! This place exudes the rustic charm of ‚Äúkelong‚Äù, a Malay word that describes an offshore platform built by fishermen for fishing, which are commonly found in the coastal areas surrounding neighbouring countries such as Malaysia, the Philippines and Indonesia. 

I heard that a handful of ‚Äúkelong‚Äù remain around Singapore, but they are supposed to be out there somewhere in the seas. Yet, I discovered one right inside a park in a residential estate! 

William

Sembawang is one of the few places in Singapore that unless you live there, you will not make a trip over. Besides the only Hot Spring in Singapore, Sembawang park is worth a visit too.

Sometimes we can see people spreading fishing net over the sea, a sight seldom see nowadays. Within the park there's Beaulieu House which is built in 1910s, now a Chinese Seafood restaurant?

It's a small park, but there are places like a  Kampong style mosque,  cycling paths, a Peranakan restaurant within landed properties, colonial houses, etc.

<358> ‚ÄúTeleported Colonial Building!‚Äù

At first glance, it looked as if a colonial house from more than a hundred years ago has been teleported to the present times!

The truth is this pair of Edwardian era (1901-1910) semi-detached houses known as Winsland House II at Penang Road (near Dhoby Ghaut)has existed since the  1910s. While its surroundings had completely transformed, it has stood the test of time.

William

Once filled with coconut plantations and used as a weekend retreat by wealthy city dwellers, Katong developed into a residential suburb by the early 20th¬†century. It became populated by a growing English-educated middle class, including Peranakans* and Eurasians.
„ÄÇ
The neighbouring Joo Chiat area is named after Chew Joo Chiat, a wealthy Chinese landowner in the early 20th¬†century. The area‚Äôs identity is especially shaped by its unique pre-war architecture ‚Äì colourful two-storey shophouses and terrace houses with ornate facades, intricate motifs and ceramic tiles.
„ÄÇ
*The term is an Indonesian/Malay word that means ‚Äúlocal born‚Äù, which generally refers to people of Chinese and Malay/Indonesian heritage.

Dreaming of another staycation at the @mo_singapore ‚ú® Lately I‚Äôve found myself watching back my IGTV with snippets from our stay and wishing I could go back in time... ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Now that travel is off the table, I‚Äôll try to spend a couple of days enjoying a staycation in Singapore every so often to take a mental break from 2020. üáßüá∑ Sonhando com outra staycation no Mandarin Oriental ‚ú® Esses dias me peguei assistindo o IGTV que postei com uns pedacinhos das nossas ~mini f√©rias~ e deu uma saudade... Agora que viajar parece algo que a gente fazia em outra vida, quero tentar passar uns 2 dias num hotel de vez em quando pra pelo menos lembrar como era a sensa√ß√£o de acordar em outro lugar.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Pode parecer besteira (e um desperd√≠cio) pagar por um hotel na sua pr√≥pria cidade, mas num ano em que todos os meses se misturam numa coisa s√≥, uma mudan√ßa de cen√°rio e rotina ajuda a renovar as energias. J√° estou pensando quando vai ser a pr√≥xima üòç #SeteMilKmEmSingapura‚†Ä
‚†Ä

Estou falando da realidade de Singapura, onde os casos est√£o sob controle, as medidas sanit√°rias, de rastreamento/isolamento s√£o exemplares, tem multas pra pessoas e estabelecimentos que n√£o cumprem as regras etc. Mesmo com a vida por aqui entrando num "novo normal" (como odeio esse termo! üòÇ), s√≥ postei 6 fotos nos √∫ltimos 6 meses porque a √∫ltima coisa que quero √© incentivar algu√©m a se arriscar. ‚†Ä

Mas pa√≠ses e cidades diferentes t√™m realidades diferentes e infelizmente vai ser assim por muito tempo... Posso fazer um post detalhando as medidas que est√£o nos ajudando a viver de uma forma mais tranquila por aqui, me digam se interessa a algu√©m ou se s√≥ a nerd aqui acha isso interessante? üòÜ

Joo Chiat & Katong are places in Singapore that are rich in culture & heritage! Apart from the well-known Peranakan shophouses with their colourful motifs and famous food havens like Katong Laksa, you will find many hidden gems like the Former Queen's Theatre.

Besides Joo Chiat & Katong, we hope you had a great time rediscovering other places in Singapore. If you haven‚Äôt, do join us for the #SingapoRediscovers photography contest! All you have to do is to visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured in the itinerary and share at least 2 original shots captured in your own style. Click on the link in our bio to check out the itinerary!
 
3 steps to take part in the contest:
1. Share with us what rediscovering Singapore means to you in the post caption
2. Follow @sgig and @stb_sg on Instagram
3. Hashtag #SGIGRediscovers #SingapoRediscovers and a gentle reminder to make your account public so we are able to track your submissions!

Your submissions do not necessarily have to showcase the interior of the featured locations - any "hidden spots" within the precincts are welcome (the listed locations in the itinerary are just examples) A gentle reminder to exercise judgment and practise discretion when capturing these images too!

Winners will stand a chance to win the following attractive prizes:

1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)
3rd Prize: 2 x Tickets to Universal Studios Singapore (worth up to SGD $162)

Consolation Prizes:
4 x #InstaWalk Bugis, Waterloo and Kampong Gelam Tribe Tours (worth $55 per ticket) and
3 x Tickets to Trick Eye Museum Singapore (worth up to $25 per ticket)

More info on the contest and its T&Cs can also be found on our link in bio.

Contest ends 4 October 2020, 2359 hours (GMT+08:00).

„ÄêAng Mo Kio #2 - Wanton Mee„Äë
Feeling artsy? Then you really have to make a trip to the hawker centre at block 724. Beside the vibrantly-painted walkways and stone tables, check out the wall murals at the side of some of the iconic buildings in AMK-hood that have been around since the 80s.

Since we have covered the Singapore-style Wanton Mee two years ago, it's time we work on the next most popular style - Pontian Wanton Mee. This wanton mee chain is almost everywhere in Singapore now. This version of Pontian-style wanton mee comes with a savoury black sauce served with a fried dumpling. 

#dabaogram decided to give Pontian Wanton Mee a more refreshing look. We torched the BBQ pork, re-arranged the noodles, baked the leaves of the vegetables to give them a more crispy texture and topped our creation with some spring onions and flowers. Viola!

We would like to thank Pontian Wanton Mee for bringing these yummy bowls of noodles from across the Causeway. It means so much to us now especially when we are not able to travel, not even Johor Bahru. This is an un-sponsored series in which we hope to raise awareness of our rich local hawker food culture and help local hawkers during this unprecedented period. Join us on this journey of rediscovery where we dabao and transform our local favourites into works of gastronomic art, one district at a time. Tag us in your post if you would try your own ‚Äòdabaogram‚Äô at home. 

Singapore, fried rice paradise? See ya next week!

"Kampong life"
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singapore‚Äôs mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each other‚Äôs presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkok‚Äôs postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Sembawang Hot Spring Park

The entrance of Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Sembawang Hot Spring Park is located in SingaporeSembawang Hot Spring Park
Type	Hot spring
Location	Sembawang, Singapore
Nearest town	Yishun
Coordinates	1.4344¬∞N 103.8224¬∞ECoordinates: 1.4344¬∞N 103.8224¬∞E
Area	1.1 hectares (11,000 m2)
Opened	4 January 2020; 8 months ago
Owned by	NParks
Public transit access	 NS13  Yishun
Facilities	Hot spring
Website	Official website
The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring and a public park in Singapore.
It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, and its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser and Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership and potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle and bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020.
It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

‚ÄúSpent the weekend exploring Marina Bay and the many gems it has to offer with my family. One of our first stops was the Singapore Flyer. Each rotation lasts for 30 minutes and the view was simply breathtaking. 
 
From the flyer you can see up to 45km away, that‚Äôs basically a view of the whole island for you to take in. I felt really relaxed while I was up there, and my children loved it too!
 
I would highly recommend visiting the flyer. Come on, do you really want to miss out on one of the best views in Singapore?‚Äù

Date: Saturday, 17 October 2020‚Å£
Time: 14.00 - 17.00‚Å£
Instructor: Hairul Latiff‚Å£
Location: 727 North Bridge Road #02-01, Singapore 198695‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Course Fee: SGD35‚Å£
Price inclusive of tools and materials‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Join us to experience a printmaking session where you will be introduced to the basics of linocut carving and printing techniques. You will begin by tracing the selected pattern or design and transferring them onto the lino surface. Then, using various linocut blades, you will carve the lino block to create a positive image. Finally, you will ink the image using a brayer with block printing ink and print the image onto paper.‚Å£

[Sembawang Precinct] Rediscover Sembawang hot spring with super grandma

Rediscovery is about going to a known place with a local "expert" and then appreciate the way of enjoyment of the place

Always go with an local ‚Äúexpert‚Äù when doing exploration. Come explore with super grandma Mdm Tan  to the only hotspring in Singapore. Just bring the essentials all in a plastic bag like a true blue Singapore veteran . She brought a pail, a scoop and a towel. That is all you need to enjoy the hot spring. 

If you want some better protection, you can bring an umbrella. For a complete experience, you can also bring some eggs to do hard boiled eggs with the hotspring water. 

This is the next best alternative to travelling for hotspring.

Another spot at #ToaPayoh Central that has transformed over the years.

The spot where the local @courtssg outlet occupied used to be the post office which in front of it stood a sculpture of a man lifting a woman, although I am quite sure the post office was not the first occupant of the old building.

The two housing blocks at the back of the picture used to be two of four accommodated the athletes competing in the 1973 SEAP Games.

Lastly, the two-storey building on the right of the picture used to house the local outlet of the now-defunct Emporium (Ëã±‰øùËâØ) departmental store.

The Japanese Cemetery was a place I really wanted to visit post circuit breaker, and I‚Äôm glad I did. Build not only to commemorate various renowned Japanese figures who made an impact on Singapore, the place offers a gorgeous space that many can revel in whilst paying respects to the fallen.  I even got chance to interact with the janitor, who says he cleans the cemetery without fail everyday. Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. It‚Äôs an opportunity to re-live our nation‚Äôs history while tuning into modern narratives of ‚Äúhidden‚Äù spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] Reflection of Joo Chiat‚Äôs best ambassadors¬†

Rediscovery is about having a good listening ear  and keen observation of the place and people.

Joo Chiat is a place with a rich history. We often see elderly around. Some leisurely walking around while others cycle. What is unique is the friendliness of the people. I was there twice recently. On both occasions, I have had elderly (residents or former residents) who came to chitchat with me about the heritage of the place as well as interesting places to shoot. They seem to be the best ambassadors of the place - For their knowledge and their part in the history of this place- to help us rediscover Singapore.

This is a reflection ( literally) of the elderly from Joo Chiat with the colorful peranakan house

7-8 years ago (I think), I came here alone and explored this north part of #singapore with a deep history of #colonial past. Things have remained pretty much the same - there has been no upgrade or redevelopment to this area in #seletar which used to house British military staff. Nonetheless,  the bungalows are one of a kind with double chimneys and even with maid chambers. They are probably beautiful and glorious in the olden days, and though old and derelict and abandoned now, they look as beautiful amidst nature looking to take over the houses. Given their long abandoned state, there is also something eerie about the windows, I can imagine pairs of eyes looking out! Hahaha . I wouldn't dare to explore the insides of the houses, despite my curiosity.  Some of the houses (those with glass panels and are refurbished) are now for commercial use. Within the surroundings, there are also many interesting streets with #british #streetnames such as Hyde Park (the last time I visited, it was barricaded for redevelopment) and Oxford Street, a huge reminder of our colonial past. For now, I can also make pretend that I am travelling in the UK üòÅü§£ oh ya, check out the super unique tree in the first picture! Have never seen anything quite like it!

Hydrotherapy
Natural Spring Water
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

According to local geologists, the exact source of the spring remains unknown, but it is believed that its origin may be southwest of its actual location, possibly at Bukit Timah. Hot springs are formed when underground water comes into contact with hot rock masses. The resulting high pressure causes the water to seep upwards through cracks, forcing itself out of the ground as a spring.

A series of tests conducted by the PSB Corporation and SGS Testing & Control Services found the spring water contains 420 mg of chloride per litre, an amount which is substantially higher than the 35 to 100 mg in the water from Choa Chu Kang & Bedok waterworks. It was also found that the sulphide content is three times more than tap water & the spring water is also slightly alkaline due to the presence of minerals. Natural spring waters may have health benefits, similar to the hot springs of other countries near tectonic plates with volcanoes, in a search for cures for some skin conditions, as well as debilitating ailments like rheumatism & arthritis. Although local rheumatologists conceded that hydrotherapy is an accepted treatment that can be helpful for mild forms of rheumatism or muscle strain, they, along with dermatologists, remain skeptical of claims about the alternative healing of the natural spring water.

Hot hard water bubbles continuously in the well, releasing a slightly unpleasant sulphur mud-like odour together with steam. The temperature of the spring water is measured by precision instrument to be constant 70 ¬∞C (160 ¬∞F). In an investigation carried out by the Nanyang Technological University in 1994, the hot spring was found to have an estimated yield of approximately 150 litres (33 imp gal; 40 US gal) per minute at ground level through installed steel casings.

A compilation of the beautiful house of Tan Teng Niah; 
Built in 1900, the former house of Tan Teng Niah is the last surviving Chinese villa in Little India. Tan Teng Niah was a¬†towkay¬†(Chinese businessman of good standing) Many believe that Tan built the house for his wife and that the inscription referred to her.¬†The design of the house were beautifully crafted including the main door inscription made just for his wife. Note of the blossom flowers on the windows. The former house of Tan Teng Niah has eight rooms.

To the Chinese, the house design was auspiciously designed. Each doorway was beautifully decorated with carvings including the twirling wooden stairway of the golden dragons which impressed me most. The carvings were so detailed, precise and elegantly designed. Kudos to the 1900s skillful carpenters. 

The house was restored and conserved in the 1980s for commercial use, and the restoration project was awarded the Singapore Institute of Architects Honourable Mention in 1991. It is partially rented out Mr Chandran who had been there for more than 10years. He is a retired police officer whom set up this flower bussiness. I  was fortunate to have him sharing of his experiences and allowing me to take the beautiful interior of the villa.

Festive Colours

Campbell Lane, situated just a street (Serangoon Road) from the ever popular Tekka Market, is a popular destination for locals and tourists alike. From my various visits (actually only twice in the last 2 weeks), it's always crowded and this is despite COVID still being a prevalent problem here in Singapore today. Its prime location between the Indian Heritage Centre and the Little India Arcade makes it a popular shopping street.

Walking along Campbell Lane, one may find themselves amongst garlands and other items that one may need for the Hindu festive season. Despite COVID-19, the festive mood is still present in Little India and many Hindu devotees still walk the streets of Little India looking for festive goods.

The Mid-Autumn Festival means more than just lanterns and mooncakes to me, it's a celebration of tradition, culture and time spent with the family. 

As per tradition, we spent a full day at Chinatown, amidst the smells and the sounds we ate a hearty lunch and strolled passed the usual routes. Bought somethings here and there and visited the Buddha's tooth temple.  Following that we returned home to a comforting and lively family gathering at grandma's place in celebration of the Mid-Autumn Festival. 

It's hard to get time with everyone in our hustle bustle life but just a simple meal with the ones you love is all that you need. 

Photos are in the back after the video.

#deskerroad is located within the Rochore planning area in the Central Region of Singapore.1 This stretch of road was built after the completion of land reclamation works in the old Kampong Kapor area.2 It is laid out in an orthogonal (at right angles) manner between two main roads ‚Äì Serangoon Road and Jalan Besar.3 It was named after Andre Filipe Desker, a former resident of the area and butchery owner in the 1860s.4 

Once notoriously known as a ‚Äúred-light area‚Äù,5 Desker Road still retains its old-world charm with its rows of conserved terrace shophouses lining some parts of the road.6 In addition, it is the site where 88 flats under the public housing programme were built by the Housing and Development Board (HDB) in 1982.7 The prevailing vibrant landscape of Desker Road is linked to other commercial developments such as condominiums, restaurants, shopping and hotels, located within the areas around Jalan Besar, reflecting the current needs of the population it now serves.

Not even the rain can stopped me from taking photos anymore‚Ä®‚Ä®The last couple of #instawalk tours with @tribetours were met with bad weather. And what a juggling act I had to perform, sheltering myself under the brolly, angling my phone to demonstrate the shots and grabbing the mic to share what goes on behind the screen, I‚Äôve actually grown a liking to rainy days

For starters, the weather was a lot more bearable. The rain brings some kind of drama to the photos, creating a different kind of mood compared to a bright sunny day. It also teaches me to balance my props, and utilising them

I love how well coordinated my boots and brolly are in this shot. Not forgetting, puddles of water creating the perfect reflections

There's a new premium salon on the block. Enso Hair Studio is the go-to salon in the heart of Singapore's CBD. They're aiming for the stars, carving a place in Singapore's hair industry underneath the towers of Raffles City. The hair artists are skilled at providing hair solutions such as hair styling, hair colouring, blowouts, hair texturing, as well as hair and scalp care. Need a proper perm? Hey there! Origin Journeys is a new platform for authentic experiences in Singapore, allowing you to connect with grassroots businesses and to really be able to appreciate what our country is about. More so than that, we hope to be a force for good by channelling leisure dollars where they matter the most. Origin Journeys was conceived during this difficult period of Covid, where we went back to the drawing board and asked ourselves what travel and leisure really meant. The idea of looking at our immediate surroundings with fresh perspectives, since we're gonna be stuck here for awhile üíÅüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è, re-discovering our roots, tapping into narratives of our individual and collective heritages and being able to offer unique, personalised and homegrown experiences guided by the most knowledgeable and affable locals was foremost in our minds.

From short weekend escapades to deeper journeys into rediscovering the little nooks of our city, we offer experiences for all ages and personalities, thoughtfully crafted through our years of scouring this island for the absolute best it has to offer. 

Keep a lookout at this space for our upcoming launch campaign where you get a chance to win exciting experiences, meals at the hottest spots and a night or two at the most luxurious hotels in town!

#SingapoRediscovers - 24 Sept 2020

<353> ‚ÄúProbably one of the liveliest places in the heartland of Singapore‚Äù

This is a high-ceiling sheltered alley that is lined with a large diversity of small shops that provide every daily need and service you can imagine at the most affordable prices. 

Its most unique feature is the temporary stalls that are set up outside the shops where the sellers promote all sorts of interesting things of the season. 

The place is always bursting at seams in the weekends from morning to the evening. Lured by its local vibes, even on a weekday, there is no short of human traffic.

I would confidently say that it is probably one of the liveliest shopping arcades in the heartland of Singapore. If you drop by, let me show you around.

William

Did you know that the former house of Tan Teng Niah is the last surviving Chinese villa in Little India?

This is the first time I‚Äôve actually explored Little India and glad that I‚Äôve taken some photos of this unique place as a souvenir. 

There was even a friendly man telling me where I should take my photos and led me to a flock of pigeons which I‚Äôve failed to capture the scene nicely because I didn‚Äôt have the right lens setup at that time.

I would say this is the most fruitful photography session I‚Äôve done in Singapore. I am also glad to have my first shoot this year (though tired of clocking 12k steps in that few hours) as the pandemic has kept us at home for the most part of the year.

This place is probably the most common thing you have ever seen in your Instagram and Facebook feed right now! üòÇ so I gonna compile everything into one post so I won‚Äôt spam you guys as well! We shot this on the second day of opening and we did a reservation before heading so take note! This place is inspired by the pantheon in Rome and it‚Äôs located at Marina Bay Sands! 

Tips when heading there : 
1) Remember to reserve your slot and timing online at the Apple website and one email is entitled to two person. 
2. Head there early even thou you might need to wait for awhile but it‚Äôs always good to be early then late.
3. There will be an Apple staff bringing you around and this tour is around 15 mins so for those people who wanna shoot, do know what‚Äôs the angle and view you wanna shoot so go there aim and go if not you have to come back another day! üòÇüòÇüòÇ

Set in the heart of the city, the art-centric Ritz-Carlton Millenia Singapore surrounds you with visual beauty. Admire the sweeping view of the Marina Bay cityscape from the 32nd floor, or the 4,200 masterpieces by world-renowned artists like Frank Stella, Dale Chihuly and Andy Warhol, housed within this luxurious 5-star establishment.

Treat your eyes to a feast during your stay with five culinary presentations daily, or a trip to the nearby Gardens By The Bay with the complimentary limousine drop-off service.

Created an illustration of Raffles Hotel Singapore to pay tribute to Sir Stamford Raffles and to celebrate Mid Autumn Day.

Raffles hotel is a hotel established in 1887, is one of the greatest 19th century hotel in the world.

At Raffles Hotel, you can enjoy a hearty meal with beverages and bakery, indulge in the stunning scenery in the park, embracing the experience of shopping at raffles boutique, explore the charm of the courtyards, admiring the striking architecture and the heritage. 

I hope to convey a sense of place and emotion through this illustration of @raffleshotelsingapore. Happy Mid Autumn Day !

‚ÄúAlong the Marina Bay Waterfront Promenade lies a hidden gem that is missed by most ‚Äì the Red Dot Design Museum. 
 
What I love about this place is the Design Shop where carefully curated design objects from around the world can be found. There are even ones produced by Singapore designers! It‚Äôs a perfect place if you‚Äôre looking for a gift ‚Äì they have a variety of items ranging from scarves, fountain pens to cardholders!
 
If you‚Äôre taking a walk along the area, do pop by to check it out. For non-Muslim friends, they even have a Museum Cafe Bar to dine at with a good view!‚Äù

2020 has been an absolute rollercoaster of a year, as the world recovers from a depression ‚Äî both literally and figuratively. This only makes festive occasions all the more precious, as we realise who the most important people in our lives are: family.

Being the only immediate kin I have, my mother has been the person I've spent the most time with over the last few years. This year has made that the case even more so, due to us being responsible people and staying home almost 24/7.

Taking the time to head out to Chinatown was a welcome break from the routine of staying home, made even more special by her agreeing to be photographed ‚Äî trust me, this is especially rare.

As such, I'll be spending this Mid-Autumn Festival 2020 with the most important person in my life, as she rounds out her last few decades here with me.

Trithemis aurora, the crimson marsh glider, is a species of #dragonfly in the family Libellulidae. It is a medium-sized dragonfly that is commonly found in weedy tanks and ponds, marshes, channels, and slow flowing streams and rivers in the lowlands and mid-hills. It breeds in streams, rivers, canals, ponds and tanks. (Source: Wikipedia)

Something I've always enjoyed about night photography is experimentation with long exposures. I love the effect I get with clouds, moving water and of course, light trails with moving objects.

To envision with your mind's eye and then be able capture what the eye is unable to physically see is truly satisfying. Using photography to capture more than just light - capture time and space.
