Today is the last day to join us for the #SingapoRediscovers photography contest in collaboration with Singapore Tourism Board!

All you have to do is to check out our itinerary (link in bio), visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured and share at least 2 original shots captured in your own style. We‚Äôve included example photo spots in the itinerary, but your photos can be captured at other spots as well! These can be carousel-style posts or separate posts.

3 steps to take part in the contest:
1. Share with us what rediscovering Singapore means to you in the post caption
2. Follow @sgig and @stb_sg on Instagram
3, Hashtag #SGIGRediscovers #SingapoRediscovers.

You will stand a chance to win the following attractive prizes:

1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)
3rd Prize: 2 x Tickets to Universal Studios Singapore (worth up to SGD $162)

Consolation Prizes:
 4th, 5th, 6th, 7th prizes: 4 x #InstaWalk Bugis, Waterloo and Kampong Gelam Tribe Tours (worth $55 per ticket)
8th, 9th and 10th prizes: 3 x Tickets to Trick Eye Museum Singapore (worth up to $25 per ticket)

For more info on the contest and its T&Cs, please click on the link in bio.

Contest ends 4 October 2020, 2359 hours (GMT+08:00).

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Katong / Joo Chiat precinct

In Katong Joo Chiat area, you can discover conserved heritage shophouses with Peranakan culture or influence /designs.

Although this area is very well known for it's colourful street, Koon Seng Road, Katong Joo Chiat precinct, has other good attractions as well.

1. Teong Theng Co is a old school crafted rattan based furniture maker that has 70 years of history in Joo Chiat.  This is a good time to rediscover, some of our heritage shops and at the same time, feels the nostalgic vibes

2. China Collection (antique) shop is painted blue and white and this Chinese shop house  has now turn itself into a modern building with a minimal twist. Those who likes minimal design will appreciate the paint work

3. I couldnt resist taking a shot of this old school hair salon, everytime I pass by

4. Rumah Bebe in Katong is a Peranakan heritage boutique, a school, a bake shop and also a mini museum. I simply love the interior (more like exterior) decor.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] - Traditional Popiah

Rediscovery is about walking and finding unique place. ¬†

As I rediscovered Joo Chiat, I came across Kway Guan Huat Joo Chiat - a traditional¬† Popiah maker since 1938 I was intrigued by the skill of those making the traditional popiah skin from dough. Great to see Chinese Fujian food culture still active and alive for over 80 years. It is also interesting to note that it coexisted for so many years next to the Malay enclave ( Geylang Serai) - Another reminder of our unique racial harmonious culture of Singapore.¬†

1. Marina South Pier to St. John's Island (9.00am), then take the shuttle ferry from St. John's to Sisters' Island (10.00am)

3. Kusu Island to St. John's Island (1.00pm/2.30pm)
4. Explore St. John's Island, 15-20min walk to Lazarus Island
5. St. John's Island back to Marina South Pier (4.00pm/6.00pm)
.

This is the only village left in SG. Pretty unique and memorable one for many of the locals.
Me as a Malaysian, this is truly a nostalgia.
Like most early childhood memories, the rest of my kampung recollections are spare, fragmented, truncated; the equivalent of cinematic stills, with no soundtrack, no entertaining stories. Still, the few images that come to mind are vivid, enduring. The rough concrete floor of my grandmother's house; the splintered texture of the wooden walls, the chickens running free around the compound, the rickety chicken coop that I once tried to climb and nearly fell off the well with its column of cold damp air enclosed by stone.

Hike in the city at Fort Canning.

Since we‚Äôre encouraged to be local tourists, we decided on a hike at Fort Canning Park. üí°Here‚Äôs a tip for parents, print the map üó∫ from NParks and make your kids the ‚Äútour guide‚Äù, with Jubilee Park as the last stop so they‚Äôll press on for the PLAY incentive!
 
There are nine historical gardens and we explored half of them yesterday. We started at The Foothills after lunch at Clarke Quay and made our way up the Raffles Garden where we were greeted by the Fort Canning Lighthouse on top of Fort Canning Hill. Next was the Instagram worthy Sang Nila Utama Garden üå∫with Javanese split gates, recreated to resemble the 14th century royal palace gardens. We spent some time at the Artisan‚Äôs Garden which featured an archaeological dig exhibition site along with displayed artefacts that were unearthed since the 1980s. We didn‚Äôt manage to cover all 9 gardens and it‚Äôs a pity The BattleBox tour is now closed due to COVID-19 but I‚Äôm sure we‚Äôll be back again.

To conclude our day of adventure- play time at Jubilee Park which is across Liang Court. The climbing nets and long slide are now closed but thankfully the swings, see-saw, log scramble and slides at the toddler area kept the young and young at heart very happy! 

Fort Canning is easily accessible by train from Fort Canning and Clarke Quay MRT stations. Don‚Äôt forget to put on comfortable walking shoes, slap on sunscreen, mosquito repellant and go armed with a sense of adventure where you‚Äôll definitely be rewarded for a journey back in time experience!
.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] The Red House of Katong.

Rediscovery is about exploring angles and lighting of presenting the subjects. I was not very happy with shooting with the road divider( photo3)

I have visited this location a few times. Finally, I found the right lighting and angle (photo 1 and 2) to capture this iconic building. 

The Red House Bakery is a popular reference to the iconic confectionery shop, Katong Bakery & Confectionery. It was a popular breakfast place amongst Singaporeans living in the eastern part of Singapore, especially for its signature cakes and curry puffs. It was established in 1925 but closed on 23 March 2003 after the shophouse where it was occupying was deemed as unsafe. It has since reinvented itself. Currently, it houses a bakery cafe - Micro Bakery & Kitchen Red House

‚ÄúWith a rich culture and amazing cuisine, Peranakans are known for their colourful heritage shophouses and intricate tiles. Beyond this row of vibrant architecture, Joo Chiat is great for food and a chill day of exploration!

To match these houses, I was reminded of the mooncakes from @thelapisplacesingapore, a creation that pushed boundaries and modernised the Kueh Lapis into a contemporary treat. The fusion of pastel-coloured snow skin on a rainbow-coloured Kueh Lapis that offers a twist to tradition ‚Äì and a new way for me to explore Singapore.‚Äù 

Captured by @stormscape for #SingapoRediscovers. More in our Instagram Stories!

There's a little fruit shop inside Tekka Market and it belongs to our friend Annie. The market which they are located in has quite a storied past. Tekka means "bamboo clumps" in Mandarin and was named after the bamboo that grew on either side of the canal. It was frequented by people from the working class, hence it became known as the "people's market". 

The original market across the road was demolished in 1982. Most of the store-holders, including Annie and family, relocated to the Tekka market that we know today. 

Our support for local businesses also mean this is the time when we will stop by and have some tropical fruits. We introduce you to fruits that are in season so you can have them at their absolute best (don't worry, durians not included üòÇ). This family business was started by her grandparents and has been in operations for more than 40 years, so its safe to say they know their stuff.

Took some time this week to visit the Little India precinct a.k.a. Tekka. As I strolled around, I bumped into this colorful house, which is known as the Former House of Tan Teng Niah. This colorful house is the last surviving Chinese Villa in the area, and the story inspires me a lot because it displayed how the small Chinese industries operated alongside the Indian cattle and rattan trade.

I then walked around the area a little bit more and never got bored of it. It always surprised me. For instance, I found a lot of beautiful murals such as the Cattleland 2, which shows several cows interacting with each other in different activities and created that sense of community.

"Pretty enjoyable exploration!", I must say. A place worth visit to everyone who wants to learn about what it means to have culture strongly amplified through the sense of diversity and belonging.

Karma is an action, not a result. The future is not set in stone as you can change the course of your life at this very moment by changing your intentional acts and self-destructive patterns.

Karma is energy and it‚Äôs our intentional thoughts and actions. The energy we generate now and in the future will affect us. It has nothing to do with reward or punishment. 

For us, our karma is treating life as big collaboration. Individually, we are one drop. 
Together, we are an ocean.
Daily, in your own little ways, the best we can all do is stay positive, support each other and put a smile on the face of people around. 

Kindness, Positivity, Support, Collaboration always win.
Anger, Negativity, Resentment, Jealousy ... well we don't care about the outcome as they are ignored and dismissed.

Stay positive! Keep communucating with your loved ones and we will go through this 2020 year all fine üôèüèº

Observe the grand Silver Chariot Procession and you'll see that Deepavali is a humble celebration between family and friends as well. post_caption:
Happy Mid-Autumn Festival everyone! May your personal and professional life be blessed with moments of joy and happiness! 

Come over to Qian Hu Fish Farm and celebrate with us!

Also, head over to our ecommerce store at https://www.qianhushop.sg/ today! 

https://www.qianhushop.sg/ offers you a wide range of aquarium and pet accessories!
 
Here are some interesting findings about the festival:
According to some experts, the Mid-Autumn Festival was traditionally a time to express gratitude to the gods. It is also a time of year that the moon is at its brightest. This explains why lunar legends have always been attached to the celebration. 

I trust many of us are aware of the story of Chang Er, the wife of a merciless king who drank the elixir of immortality he had intended to drink, so as to save her people from his tyrannical rule.
It is believed that she has ascended to the moon upon her brave act, and has been worshipped by the Chinese as a Moon Goddess ever since.

Many would enjoy the occasion by attending moon-gazing parties. Family and friends would sit in gardens lit by the soft glow of paper lanterns, sip tea and nibble on mooncakes.

Children in particular love this festival as they get to tote lanterns. In the past, there were only traditional lanterns with wax candles that are made from paper. Today, there are also plastic, battery-operated versions.

Mooncakes are the main highlight of the Mid-Autumn Festival. It is believed that they helped to free Yuan China from Mongol rule, after rebels organised an uprising by passing messages hidden in these mooncakes.

Today, there are not only traditional flavours with lotus seed paste and egg yolk but also snowskin versions filled with everything from chocolate to durian. They are best enjoyed with a strong, palate-cleansing cup of Chinese tea.

Have you managed to shoot those stunning night scenes, light trails, smooth silky waters and more?

Check out my night photography workshop on Link in Bio. 

I‚Äôll coach you the basic elements of night photography, providing you with tips and techniques of low light and long exposure photography. 

We will be working on camera settings to create different effects to capture fascinating images as the day changes from twilight hour into the night. 

No filter required!

Just practical stuff from your in-camera settings.

This workshop takes place at one of Singapore's most vibrant quays along the Singapore River, within a vicinity that is surrounded by historical and modern architecture. 

The location provides you with all the required subjects of interest to photograph in low light and to acquire the skills of night photography.

Book your spot through info@carolinepang.com

Have you been to Kampong Lorong Buangkok before? 

Made up of 26 single-story wooden houses, the area is the only surviving traditional village in Singapore. 

The village also boasts some of the lowest rents in the country. According to a landlord, some individual kampong rooms cost as little as S$6.50 per month. WATCH: #linkinbio

Grandlink Square, with the front facade of the former queen's theatre.

It used to be an entertainment place until it ceased its operation in 1982. Today, the current building is occupied by Grandlink square, retaining the front facade.  The facade now is under the conservation area of URA (Urban Redevelopment Authority).

Rediscovering Sg means to walk around the neighbourhood instead of taking public transport because who knows we might spot a hidden gem at the corner of the street, which led me to this historical place.

Instead of focusing on the things that don't matter, get obsessed with who you're becoming, where you're going and all of the amazing things you're going to accomplish!

More than ever, this year in which everything has been on pause, has been the best time to do everything you always wanted to do! Your personal projects, your side-hustles, etc!

While I‚Äôve been to Chinatown - Singapore‚Äôs largest historic precinct - numerous times, I‚Äôve not had the opportunity to explore its streets much. 

Having a short stay here not only gave me the opportunity to do so, it has also helped me to reconnect with my homeland, appreciate the differences and similarities that binds us, and make me extremely proud of our progress.

Even though I have walked past many of these streets numerous times, no two walks have been the same. There‚Äôs simply too much to see/do/learn/eat/buy here. In fact, I may have been too keen to explore more of Chinatown that I‚Äôve just booked another staycay in the vicinity.

Swipe üëâüèª to check out some of my shots from morning strolls around Chinatown throughout the years.

Sometimes happiness can be so simple ‚ú®

I really miss taking campervan roadtrips and being on the road! Since it‚Äôs unlikely we‚Äôd get to travel this year, some creativity is needed to make this time count ü§îüí≠

We‚Äôve been searching for ulu roads in SG with a scenic view where we can park the car and live a pretend ‚Äúvanlife‚Äù even if just for a few hours. After checking out a few spots, it‚Äôs usually can park no view / got view can‚Äôt park / got view can park but super crowded and we‚Äôre starting to think it‚Äôs impossible... until we unexpectedly drove into this small park! It was exactly what we were looking for - quiet spot right by the waters of Seletar reservoir, overlooks the dam and wait for it... free parking! üòÇüôåüèº

We popped open the boot, sat down and made tea. It turned out to be a simple, perfect kinda night.

Taking a solo trip down to Little India alone last weekend to rediscover Singapore made me realise all the little things I overlook in life.

I had less pressure with time when I roamed around alone, and had the tenacity to speak to the people in the neighborhood. I learnt so much more when I spoke to the locals - Knowing why they came here for, what their struggles were (especially during this pandemic), their dreams and even the history of the places around us. And I truly miss traveling (solo) for the same reasons!

I don‚Äôt usually post carousels, but these pictures truly piece together a beautiful set of stories of what Little India is all about - A mix of old and new, people, culture, art and history.

1. A box of vintage old films outside Sajeev Digital Studio

2. The studio upstairs, where foreign workers take portraits to send home the pictures for their families to matchmake them with potential wives

3. Sajeev Digital Studio from outside

4. An Indian foreign lady, named Mary, who works outside a pop-up stall at House of Tan Teng Niah (the colorful house 2 posts before). She‚Äôs making prayer garlands using Jasmine, Rose, Orchid and Marigold and has been here for over 10 years

5. Massive mural which juxtaposes modern vehicles and the old-school way of transporting tiffins. Lorry as scale

6. Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple, Singapore‚Äôs oldest hindu temple that is dedicated to the goddess and destroyer of evil, Sri Veeramakaliamman or Kali. Early Migrant workers worship this goddess for safety in this new foreign land

This is the longest caption I have ever had, made with time, sweat, with sore legs and neck. Would appreciate it if you drop a comment below and tell me which photo caught your attention the most. Keep exploring, everyone!

[Kampong Gelam Precinct] - Sultan Mosque Re-discovered

Rediscovery is about understand the historical significant of the place  and the finding suitable lighting moments to capture it so that there is clear message to communicate.

Previously, I have taken photo of Sultan Mosque in different lighting conditions. Decide to re-discover¬† the iconic Sultan Mosque in the late morning when the dome of the mosque is brightly reflected with the glory of sun‚Äôs ray together with a deep blue sky. A hope to capture a shot that remind us that the future ahead will be brighter for Singapore - we need to stay strong together

This place used to be crowded with tourists and locals. Since the Covid19 pandemic, you see much fewer crowds, and thus opportunity for a cleaner shot without distracting elements. This is the best chance to re-discover the place again before the crowd returns ;)¬†¬†

We are staying home this weekend, but here's a throwback to our @sentosa_island visit last weekend where we bought tonnes of goodies from @candyliciousshop! 
.
If you don't already know, there's a storewide sale at Candylicious now (swipe to see some of the stuff on sale!) and we went crazy loading up on discounted chocolates and candies. Regular items are discounted at 25% but some are sold at substantial discounts (up to 70% off) as they're close to expiry dates like end-October. My family are chocoholics, so we got some of the heavily discounted chocolates and within a week our purchases were already half gone üòÖ We've always liked the variety of chocolates and candies at Candylicious, and they sure bring in a lot of interesting and good quality stuff.
.
The gelato counter is also having a 1-for-1 promo for their medium and large cups, so the kids finally got to eat their fav Blue Sky gelato! The Annette ice-creams are also going at 2 for $5! 
.
There was a short queue to enter the store the late afternoon Saturday we were there but the shop itself wasn't too crowded at all. Not sure how long the sale will last but if you want to go, Candylicious is now only open 2-9pm Thursdays-Sundays. 
.
We had such a fun time shopping and eating, hubs says we'll need to make another trip there to get more bargains üòÜ How's your weekend going? üòâ

#beautiful #temple of the #earth #god sitting with a moat. It was raining heavily, but it is a picture of #tranquility in the raging rain. It feels like overseas, and I wish I have more time to walk about and explore rather than the 15 mins or so I visit the island every 10 years or so. 

The middle aged couple living there tending to the temple must be feeling quite isolated from life on the mainland. The uncle I spoke to says it needs getting used to. But then I was also thinking, you get a peaceful life and an island to yourselves, isnt that great? Maybe in freedom, there is also a responsibility (manning the temple), and maybe isolation and peaceful life isn't such a great thing?

Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise¬†qigong¬†before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung¬†spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...

And on the right side of the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple lies Sago Lane (Street of the Dead). 
In the past, the street was much longer and was home to funeral parlours or death houses. 
The lane's famous Chinese death houses came into existence in the late 19th century. This was the place where people near death will be left to die.
As people were superstitious and believed that it was inauspicious to die in their own home, many chose to pay a small fee to stay in these death houses to wait for their time.
Sago Lane after all is not just a lane, it is a History in itself.
.

post_caption:
Created an illustration of the famous Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, a historical temple located in the district of Chinatown. The architecture of the temple is inspired by Buddhist temples during the Tang Dynasty.

Rebecca pays a visit to the temple wearing a Mulan inspired red outfit. I wanted to inject a sense of liveliness in her clothes by painting it bold red.

She wanted to know more about Chinese culture and hope that through Singapore rediscovering temple trips, it will enable her to gain more insights about Buddhism history and culture.

Culture and Fashion

It's difficult to not notice women dressed in Kurtis -- the most widely worn women traditional attire in India -- while strolling in Little India. As seen here, they come bright in colours and with floral designs. It brings out elegance and is stylish even in today's times. It's a no wonder that even young Indian ladies would wear them out on the streets today.

1. Elderly lady and her companion outside Tekka Centre.
2. Two ladies exiting from a shophouse onto Campbell Lane.
3. A lady waving for a taxi along Serangoon Road adjacent to Buffalo Road.

Dealing with green is quite challenging.
Sometimes green in nature is overly vibrant. I sometimes reduce its intensity by lowering the saturation or by increasing its brightness. I could also shift its hue slightly to either yellow or aqua. Or I can reduce the contrast of the entire image so you can reduce the overall ‚Äúpower‚Äù of the image. In any ways, the decisions are hugely influenced by the existence of the green. This time I tried to weaken the presence of the green by strengthen the power of red to counter (opposite color hue). I achieved the aged old photo look accidentally. Very interesting experiment.

"All colours üåà on a tree!" 

Eucalyptus deglupta is a species of tall tree, commonly known as the rainbow eucalyptus, Mindanao gum, or rainbow gum that is native to the Philippines, Indonesia, and Papua New Guinea.
The rainbow effect is created as the bark peels off throughout each season, revealing the fresh, bright-green bark below.¬†As each layer of bark matures, it turns shades of blue, purple, orange, and red.

If you want to know exactly how the trees' bark becomes rainbow-hued, or to witness this beautiful rainbow eucalyptus trees, you are in luck. 

Here in Singapore, the one and only! 
The heritage Mindanao Gum Tree in Katong Park, Singapore.

-The Deities and the Dead-

I have always walked by this temple and never thought much about it apart from its distinctive Tang Dynasty design in our urban environment.

Rediscovering Singapore is how I adapt to this new change (or new normal)! While finding local iconic spots to shoot in new perspective, I discovered that the Sago Lane beside this temple was known to be the ‚ÄúDead People Street‚Äù, as the terminally ill would go to these houses to wait for death. 

The business-minded Chinese would make the upper floors of the shophouses the ‚Äúdeath house‚Äù, while the ground floor serves as a funeral parlour, and that stretch of road would be the road to send off the dead!

How many of us truly know the history and cultural heritage of these newly developed places? Anyone know more spots like this to share with me, or you would like me to explore more?

The classic landscape shot of the Marina Bay.

Singapore‚Äôs Downtown Core

‚ÄúThe only surviving traditional Chinese mansion in Singapore, House of Tan Yeok Nee, was built in the 1880s and is an interesting Teochew-style residential building with an intricate roof with almost-straight ridges and wooden carvings. It‚Äôs just a small detour from Dhoby Ghaut and Fort Canning Hill! 

Teochew mooncakes come to my mind when I visit this Teochew private residence. Uniquely different from the other mooncakes, Teochew mooncakes are made with structurally layered, flaky puff pastry that signifies harmony and deep-fried to give it a golden-brown shade. Each mooncake is filled with lotus seed, mung bean, yam paste and salted duck egg yolk, such as this one from @mitzosg.‚Äù

Captured by @stormscape as part of #SingapoRediscovers ‚Äì tell us if you‚Äôve ever tried a Teochew mooncake in the comments below.

The Baobabs, Flower Dome
5 October - 1 November

Make your way into an urban oasis and take respite amidst the luscious shades of green and sweet floral scents.

The sight of the brilliantly coloured macaws instantly captures our attention, as do the beautiful blooms of the bamboo orchid, a native species that is used extensively in the landscapes of our metropolitan city-state. Man is innately attracted to nature and seeks to make connections with other life forms. This affinity with the natural world is known as ‚Äúbiophilia‚Äù, meaning ‚Äúa love of life‚Äù in Greek.

The transformation from a Garden City to City in a Garden and the movement towards City in Nature have seen the integration of biophilic design into our concrete jungle. Treelined streets, skyrise greenery and world-class gardens and parks that teem with a diversity of flora and fauna are a reflection of how Singapore has successfully incorporated nature and its ecosystem into the urban fabric, integrating both harmoniously. These efforts have not only increased biodiversity in the city, but also influenced the way we work and play.

Redesign your work and living spaces by simply introducing some plants! Beyond their aesthetic value, plants also create a restorative environment to engage our senses, promote emotional and mental well-being, and boost productivity. Jam-packed with design and therapeutic benefits, it is no surprise that many have been drawn to nurture their green fingers whilst working from home! If you‚Äôre new to introducing nature to your home or workspace, a good starter option would be the air plant, a low maintenance houseplant that can be used as a table centrepiece or hanging ornament. Alternatively, the use of cut flowers like the exotic birds of paradise seen on display can liven up your space effortlessly!

Also the cheery and colorful sight of these buildings, that mark the district area of Bugis, now long gone, are bound to evoke a sense of #nostalgia for those in the know. These buildings also set the tone for future HDB flats by creating a splashing impact and timeless appreciation for them.

‚ÄúWhen the Circuit Breaker started, it was like a ghost town. It‚Äôs heartbreaking, especially for my mother, who is known to be a chatterbox.‚Äù

Tucked in the corner of Little India, @rasoolshop_sg has been selling special spice mixes blended from their family‚Äôs secret recipes for over 60 years ‚Äî even before Singapore achieved independence! They are so popular that their customers come from all over the world, even famous ones (who can‚Äôt be named üòâ).

But for the first time in all their years of operations, Shah and his mother ‚Äî the folks behind Rasool Shop ‚Äî found themselves stuck in a predicament. Business was poor, and customer footfall was low amid COVID-19.

Luckily, they managed to find new ways of reconnecting with old customers and new friends by bringing their shop online. Now, anyone can easily purchase Rasool‚Äôs spices with just one click!

Look out for Rasool‚Äôs story tomorrow at 6:30pm!

Bussiness goes on. . . Earning a living after the circuit breaker. The last of Singapore‚Äôs streetside barber start his busssiness during the phase one.

Undying dedication to his trade and a master of the art, the one old-school barber. Streetside barbers used to be a thriving industry back then. Haircuts, and shave has been his passion for the last 56 years. A "A+" classic... .
.
Mr Lee is located behind Moosehead along Telok Ayer Street and he usually opens from 10.30am-4pm from Mon-Fri and 10.30am-3pm on Sat. To make an appointment, call him at 97712146. I am so wanting to try nostril hair trim üòÑ

Here are some food and product photos that I have shot and taught in my smartphone food photography workshops.

Recently, small grocers, chefs and home-based businesses approached me for product photography, mostly related to food and fresh produce.

With no photography budget, I said I will teach them instead, with a minimal fee, which is the simplest cost effective way to do it. 

Use your smartphone.

That is, if all you need is to upload to Instagram and Facebook. Smartphone images gives you the perfect resolution for that.

Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, almost all businesses especially small self owned ones are hard hit by loss of revenues.

Nevertheless, these business owners know that visuals are important for their business growth and social media marketing.

If you are one of them and want to learn how to create product images with no frills, drop me an email at info@carolinepang.com

„ÄêAng Mo Kio #4 - Ngoh Hiang„Äë
People living in Ang Mo Kio are pampered with plethora of hawker food spread over nine major hawker centers and many other coffee shops. If you have only a day to try all the different types of hawker food in Singapore, Ang Mo Kio is definitely the place to go.

The name ‚ÄôNgoh Hiang‚Äô refers a fried meat roll filled with minced pork and prawn filling. This traditional dish is said to have originated in Fujian province in China and is named after the five-spice powder used in Chinese pork sausages.

Nowadays, we refer to Ngoh Hiang as a hawker stall selling a whole array of crispy deep-fried items, usually eaten with vermicelli for breakfast or a lunchtime treat. Century eggs, prawn crackers, fish cakes, ‚Äòguan chang‚Äô (pink-coloured sausages) and of course Ngoh Hiang are some of the popular signature items. A Ngoh Hiang meal would not be complete without the accompanying bowls of pink, gooey sweet sauce and brownish savoury chilli sauce. It is not easy to find authentic versions of this well-loved meal these days, and hawkers continue to create more innovative items to vie for more regular fans. 

What are the items you like to include in your Ngoh Hiang meal? Comment below and share with us. See you on Thursday and see where we dabao this meal from, and where you can find a wide choices of ingredients. See ya!

The Chinatown precinct holds many hidden spots to be discovered at every corner. One such spot is Sago Lane, a place where I only know it for the good food at Chinatown complex.

Did you know that the lane was named as such as there were numerous sago factories in both Sago Street and Lane during the 1840s. In the late 19th century, this area started to be populated with death houses - houses were people nearing death were left to die. Sago Lane was also lined with shops that sold items used in funerals. It was this phenomenon that led to Sago lane being dubbed as ‚Äústreet of the dead‚Äù.

Now, in its place stands Chinatown complex ‚Äì a marketplace selling lots of delicious food and household items. Near the complex, many elderly people gather and chit chat or engaged in battles of minds and wits on a game of chess. The Buddha Tooth Relic temple, on the other side of complex, is one of the more elaborately decorated temples. All these adds to the vibrancy of this area with the constant reminder of the stark contrast to its dark past. 

With all that in mind, I slowly find myself easing onto a chair nearby with the desire to soak up the atmosphere of Sago lane....

Lantern Installation: ‚ÄúRolling in Abundance‚Äù
(Supported by 78JO)
Produced by Hong Kong artist Sunny Tam of the collectible label, 78JO in collaboration with the Sun Yat Sen Nanyang Memorial Hall, ‚ÄúRolling in Abundance‚Äù is an outdoor installation featuring four large roly-poly fish lanterns. In Chinese culture, fishes (‚Äúyu‚Äù) symbolise completeness and abundance, as it is a homonym for the Mandarin word for ‚Äúabundance‚Äù (‚Äúyu‚Äù). The rounded nature of the design is doubly symbolic, as roundness (‚Äúyuan‚Äù) also sounds similar to the Mandarin word for ‚Äúreunion‚Äù (‚Äútuan yuan‚Äù), and pays homage to the full and bright mid-autumn moon. 

‚ÄúRolling in Abundance‚Äù utilises wordplay to present traditional beliefs and values in a modern context, and encourages deeper understanding and appreciation of the beauty of the Chinese language. More importantly, in these trying times, the installation embodies our hope for more abundant years to come, and gives thanks as we reunite with families and loved ones during Phase 2 of Singapore‚Äôs circuit breaker period

Date: 15 September - 11 October
Time: 10.00am - 9.00pm (daily)

Family Outing
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

I missed Kampong.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Kampong Lorong Buangkok

Kampong Lorong Buangkok is a village located in Buangkok in Hougang, Singapore. Built in 1956, it is the last surviving kampong located on Singapore Island.

Decide to do a local tour there and I met with some very friendly folks there and one even invited me to their home for a chat.

The kampong village retains the rustic beauty and it reminded me of my kampong childhood, living in my grandfather's house in Chua Chu Kang.

The kids here run freely and the  folks here are always obliging for a chat and phototaking, which is true in the kampong spirit.

You can see herbs, mango trees and even coca plant.

Along the way, we met some visitors who brought their kids to learn more about our traditional kampong heritage.

This is certainly an enjoyable  trip and would suggests everyone to experience kampong lifestyle.

Try something new this weekend and go for a walking trail with your family! MacRitchie Reservoir is a water catchment area in central Singapore. Filled with wildlife, you can take a nice relaxing walk around the lake and away from the noise of city life. In Malaysia, Sungei Lembing offers a beautiful spot to watch the sunrise as well as a majestic waterfall. Bring your family to catch the rainbow that forms every morning.¬†¬†‚Å£
‚Å£
Over in Cameron Highlands, Malaysia, cooling temperatures await in a place known as the Mossy Forest. The fog in the air guarantees a magical atmosphere for you and family, as well as the perfect setting for an impromptu photoshoot if you feel up to it!‚Å£

Lately, I've been going around the touristy/non-touristy places to take photos. This has made me to discover and learn quite a number of things along the way.

Most importantly, it forces me to think out of the box, and create new perspective of the common scenes in Singapore, so as to make my photos more interesting to look at (hopefully). 

The walks have also reminded me that Singapore is a very interesting country. Like our hawker centre where you can find food from all over the world, Singapore has places that resembles all over the world too. So no more excuses to tell myself that Singapore is a "boring" place for photography because it is definitely not one!

A tip for those who wants to try doing this. Imagine you are a visitor from overseas paying $1k on air ticket to visit Singapore. How would you have made the trip worth it?

Revisited Punggol Waterway to Coney Island on bike couple of weeks back. The Kampong Glam area was allocated to the Malay Sultan and the Muslim community according to the Raffles Town Plan which was formulated some 200 years ago.

An iconic landmark in this precinct is the Sultan Mosque - with a gold onion-shaped dome which is hard to miss.

Join us on the Kampong Glam Trishaw Experience to witness the magnificence of this national monument!

First timer at the hotspring. Heard its about 40 degrees at the foot dipping area, but I feel its more than that, as the hotspring source is already at 70 degrees. 

Most people dare not put their feet in entirely, because it really does feel like putting your foot in boiling water. I was hovering too initially, but got tired and decided to just plonk my feet in. Turned out it actually feels good. Sure does promote blood circulation because my feet became red like lobster after 30s of dipping. 

Take a container and some eggs along too to make some onsen eggs! ü•öü•öü•ö

In the past, I didn‚Äôt really thought much when walking past Sago Lane. Did you know during the early 20th century, this lane is famous for its Chinese death houses? 

People in the past were superstitious and believed dying in their own home is considered inauspicious which is why many paid to live their last moments in these houses. 

These houses were banned subsequently in the 1960s. The Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, you see today along Sago Lane was only recently built in the 2000s.

Rediscovering Singapore also brings me back to the area along Sago street, where uncles gather around for a game of chess even during this difficult times (Of course with masks on and social distancing). One of my favourite hobby in the past was to have a game of Chinese chess. It kind of brought me back to the past just by watching them engaging in their mind games. I ended up spending 30 minutes of my time watching that exciting game of chess.

Hardly in our busy work lives, we get to take a walk down these cultural places and enjoy the modern construction as well as the forgotten meaning of these places. Since we couldn‚Äôt travel for the time being, why not join me to rediscover Singapore?

Mid Autumn festival, also known as Mooncake festival is celebrated widely by the Chinese and East Asians on the 15th day of the 8th month in the Lunar calendar. This year, it is on the 1st October. 

Mooncake is one of the must have delicacies on this day. 

In Singapore, creation of mooncakes are getting more and more creative. One of which is this one, improvised to our local taste, mooncake with the ‚ÄúMao Shan Wang‚Äù durian filling.

Few weeks ago I followed @andy1um, @izmyphotos, @victorl0 and @photographyholic to the peranakan houses in Joo Chiat. It was a bright day... why these people love to roast me under the over-excited sun during a photowalk ah? üòÖ

Not sure if you notice; because of the fengshui, peranakan houses are designed symmetrically with entrance located in the centre flanked by windows on the both sides. It‚Äôs also common to have Chinese inscribed signboard hung above the main door as well as ventilation openings carved in wood with symbolic decorations.

On Koon Seng Rd, Joo Chiat, you can find the bat-shaped ventilations which actually symbolize Good Luck. Here is something I‚Äôm very sure you didn‚Äôt notice until now; swipe to see a close-up, spot the bat-shaped ventilations and compare it with the logo of @stb_sg üòâ

This Mid-Autumn Festival, @gardensbythebay is offering a brand-new festival experience - with a mixture of both online and offline programmes.

Take a stroll through the gorgeous Apricot Grove or watch the Royal Family's Walk display, which was first displayed at the Seoul Lantern Festival last year.

Another highlight of the festival is the Colonnade of Lights display which showcases 1,500 paper lanterns thoughtfully painted by the community and Gardens by the Bay's senior workers.

Besides these displays, they also offer hands-on activities such as learning how to make a snowskin mooncake or a DIY Good-Luck knot. If you're unable to make it down, you can still participate through the virtual space where exciting performances await you!

The festival and virtual programmes will be launched on 18 Sep and lasts till 4 Oct so mark your calendars now!

Entry is free so share this post with your friends and jio them for a Mid-Autumn outing!

Travel photography is not just about shooting nice places or destinations or good food. 

It is about connecting viewers to the uniqueness of the place, it‚Äôs people, it‚Äôs culture and nature. 

It is a powerful tool to create awareness of cross cultural exchanges and many more that you can achieve through travel photography. 

It is beyond camera settings and filters.

Those are the fundamentals that I will share in my travel photography workshops and coach  potential photography participants who want to learn more on travel and documentary photography.

What is travel photography to you?

Before you sign up for any of my workshops, I encourage you to read, not just reviews on my workshops, but my works as a Travel and Documentary photographer to see whether my expertise and workshops match your requirements:

üìçChijmes‚Å£‚Å£
CHIJMES (pronounced "chimes", acronym definition: Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus and ‚ÄòMES‚Äô was added intentionally to make it sounds like chimes) is a historic building complex in Singapore.‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
The complex was used as a Catholic convent since 1852, with an acquired Caldwell House which was constructed in 1840‚Äì1841, an acquired Convent Orphanage house in 1855, the Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus Chapel in 1904 and an acquired hotel complex for the girls' school in 1933. The Caldwell House, currently a wedding venue, and the Gothic-style chapel, renamed as CHIJMES Hall, currently a function hall and also a wedding venue, have both been gazetted as national monuments. The complex has been restored in 1996 for commercial purposes as a dining, shopping and entertainment centre with ethnic restaurants, shops and a function hall, providing a backdrop for musicals, recitals, theatrical performances and weddings. „ÄêAng Mo Kio #4 - Ngoh Hiang„Äë
With Singaporeans' love of crispy flavourful fried food items, no wonder Ngoh Hiang is such a popular dish here! You can find it in almost every hawker centre in Singapore. Tell us about YOUR favourite neighbourhood Ngoh Hiang stall!

Did you have a hard time figuring out how we piled up the vermicelli? Here is what we did: First, we stacked some fish cakes to make a tower and covered the entire structure with vermicelli. We then balanced the all-time-favourite crispy prawn cracker on the tower and gingerly arranged all the other ingredients on top. Reminds us of those elegant ladies' hats at the Kentucky Derby races! To add some greens to the dish, we added some leaves from our backyard. If you watched the video, you would see the pink sweet sauce make a special appearance towards the end.

We would like to thank S11 Coffee Shop Jin Long Wu Xiang stall near Cheng Sa Market for preparing and serving such wide variety of Ngoh Hiang items. This is an un-sponsored series in which we hope to raise awareness of our rich local hawker food culture and help local hawkers during this unprecedented period. Join us on this journey of rediscovery where we dabao and transform our local favourites into works of gastronomic art, one district at a time. Tag us in your post if you would try your own ‚Äòdabaogram‚Äô at home. 

We hope you‚Äôve enjoyed our tour in Ang Mo Kio so far, take part in our IG Story poll to share with us which is your favourite dish! 

Next stop, Seng Kang! See you soon!

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Kampong Lorong Buangkok

Kampong Lorong Buangkok, built in 1956, is probably the last Kampong in mainland Singapore

I decided to do a local tour there and I met with some very friendly folks, who are always obliging for a chat or phototaking

The kampong village retains the rustic beauty and it reminded me of my late uncle house's  in Pasir Ris Kampong

The kids here run freely and love it here. The 70 year old uncle I spoke to, says the family always like to gather at their mom's house on weekend

You can see herbs, mango, banana and even a coca tree here.

Along the way, we met some visitors who brought their kids to learn more about our traditional kampong heritage.

This is certainly an enjoyable  trip and would suggests everyone, to experience this kampong way of life. 

Just make sure you respect their privacy if they are not keen to have their pictures taken.

Note: Permissions have been granted to take the pictures of the residents, in their house compound, from afar.

Really admire Ms Tan Bee Hua, the current owner of Tan's Tutu Kueh. Have been her customer for years and often find myself heading down to her shop just to satisfy my Tutu Kueh cravings. My family is also a fan and Tan's Tutu Kueh is the only place we head to for authentic, pillowy Tutu Kuehs. 

In frame: Ms Tan sieving the rice flour to make it as fine as possible. Running a Tutu Kueh shop alone is tough and labour intensive! You will find Ms Tan at both outlets (Havelock Rd in the early afternoons and then she proceeds to the Clementi outlet at night). Materials have to be prepared in the morning, such as cooking the coconut in gula Melaka and preparing of peanut fillings. All these are very time consuming so I am amazed at how dedicated Ms Tan is. Plus, she mans the shops on her own so you would imagine how many Tutu Kuehs she makes a day, all by hand! 

Really hope that the culture will live on for many more years to come. Glad that nowadays with social media, younger people gaining interest for the hawker culture and local foods. Perhaps in the future, our Singaporean delicacies will be well loved worldwide.

TEOWCHEW MOONCAKES?!
The only surviving traditional Chinese mansion in Singapore, House of Tan Yeok Nee was built in the 1880s and is an interesting Teochew-style residential building with an intricate roof with almost-straight ridges and wooden carvings. It‚Äôs just a small detour from Dhoby Ghaut and Fort Canning Hill!
.
Teochew mooncakes come to my mind when I visit a Teochew-style residential building. Uniquely different from other mooncakes, Teochew Mooncake is made with structurally layered, flaky puff pastry that signifies harmony and deep-fried to give it a golden-brown shade. Each mooncake is filled with lotus seed, mung bean, yam paste and salted duck egg yolk, such as this one from Mitzo.
¬†
More features of mooncakes shot around Singapore at @stb_sg.

Nature is not a place to visit. It is home. ‚ÄîGary Snyder

Grasses and weeds have a role in the ecosystem. There are many that are pretty too! üíö

Hydrocotyle verticillata, also known as whorled pennywort, whorled marshpennywort or shield pennywort, is a flowering plant found in South and North America and the West Indies. The creeping plants with unusual leaves give it its common names. It grows in places that are marshy, boggy, and wet. Hydrocotyle verticillata is used in aquaria, where it is undemanding but prefers a good substrate, and at least moderate light. It benefits from additional carbon dioxide.(Nature's #aircleaner!) (Source: Wikipedia)

Central Fire Station
‚Å†
The Central Fire Station (CFS), also known as the Hill Street Fire Station, is Singapore‚Äôs oldest surviving fire station. Completed in 1909, the distinctive red-and-white brick building was gazetted as a national monument by the Preservation of Monuments Board in recognition of its significance in Singapore‚Äôs history. The Singapore Civil Defence force subsequently embarked on conservation and reconstruction work, including building the Heritage Gallery to commemorate the contributions and rich history of the local fire service and its firemen. The gallery is located in the oldest part of the station, and features photographs of major fires, old firefighting equipment and uniforms, interactive displays, and audio-visual presentations to engage the public. Its highlights include a 19th-century fire engine, and the 30-metre lookout tower that visitors can climb up.‚Å†
.‚Å†

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct]¬† Ancient South Indian Temple architectural with a respect for harmonious coexistence re-discovered

Rediscovery is about relooking and appreciate the coexistence of interesting elements in an environment

I learned about Sri Senpaga only recently and decided to re-discover this amazing temple built with ancient South Indian temple architectural style that flourished in the 7th-century Chola dynasty. This temple was established in the 1850s by Ceylonese Tamils from Sri Lanka which explains the differences¬† from the usual Hindu temple that I have seen.

 Two things captured my attention. Firstly, it is the ¬†21-metre tall, five-tiered structure at the main entrance that looks amazing with the glow from the morning sun. The intrigued details are very impressive.¬†
Secondly, it was the signage that says ‚ÄúAll are welcome‚Äù. You need to read the signage in detail to be impressed by how welcoming they are regardless of different race and religion. That signage as well as the temple represents what is unique about Singapore - Our harmonious¬† coexistence of different races and religions into what is Singapore.

Hope to visit this temple more

While we may already know that Katong and Joo Chiat area is famous for its #Peranakan heritage, unique history and strong food culture, it has came to my attention that in recent years, this district has also been an uptick in wall mural and street art creation. 

Like this one @KimChooKuehChang (Title: An introduction to Peranakan Culture) that is hidden at one of the back alleys of Katong and I only came to know about it recently through my IG friend, most of the murals around the area were painted for the #KatongJooChiatArtCircuit¬†(KJC Art Circuit).

Organised by The Admin SG and commissioned by the Singapore Tourism Board, the aims of #KJCArtCircuit are to allow visitors to learn more about the heritage of the #Katong and #JooChiat, and at the same time see some of its interesting historical and culture artefacts. For residents like me, we are just excited to see this area revitalise again.
.

Singapore is known for her diversity in cultures, ethnicities and religions. Due to the travel restrictions and the SingapoRediscover campaign, I have started to explore our neighbourhoods and the history behind these places.

Most locals would know about the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple in Chinatown. This Tang-styled temple is an architectural icon and I like how it contrasts against the modern city skyline in the background. 

Did you know that the street beside it has a sombre history and is known as the "Dead People Street"? Early Chinese immigrants, many of whom had no relatives, lived out their last days in the death houses here. 

Today, this area is a lively and vibrant place. Chinatown Complex is built over part of the street and many elderly folks can be seen playing chess or checkers at the communal spaces. 

Do you know about the history of your neighbourhood? How about taking this opportunity to Rediscover Singapore?

-Culture-

Built in 1900, this colorful house used to be the house of Tan Teng Niah, a businessman that owned sweet-making factories! It is situated in Little India, an area that I have only explored a few times during school trips or as a ‚Äútour guide‚Äù for my foreign friends!

What I truly miss about traveling is the freedom to roam the streets randomly and learning about the heritage and the way of life of the locals. While travel is still on hold, I am bringing this wanderlust to rediscover Singapore as I explore a different part of the country weekly, and I am not disappointed at all!

Anyone else wanna explore other parts of Singapore together?

„Äå05 Oct 2020„Äç
Have a RAWRSOME Monday! ü¶ñ
#littlehayashisushi
#momandson
#firstborn
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
We were at @rwsentosa USS last Friday. I was surprised that Sushi had so much fun and was so brave in trying out the rides! I thought we were gonna be on the carousel for 10 times to make our $66 worth it. However, he surprised me when he requested to take the roller coaster at Jurassic World (the legs dangling one). I checked many times as we were queuing to make sure he know what were taking because I was super scared. Guess what? He loved it and I was the one screaming my lungs out. He requested to go again, and refused to get off the 2nd round üòÖ#thingsmomwoulddoforkids 
He came home and told everyone that he took the rollercoaster and he protected mama because mama was screaming. Such a sweet darling! 
I am just glad to have spent some quality time with him, even if it meant messy hair, sweaty face, getting blisters on my feet, having heat rash and running around to catch the meet n greet despite my burning achilles, it is ALL WORTH IT to see how much he enjoyed himself. ‚ù§Ô∏è
If you are heading down, do remember to purchase the tickets with @mastercard to receive a complimentary halloween special mask and a gudetama notebook! Head down at 12pm to meet n greet the characters and trick n treat with the Candy Ambassadors and have early access to the rides!üéÉüëª I must say that they did a good job with the crowd control and safe distancing within the compound, because the queue was a maximum of 30min wait and we didn‚Äôt see crowds anywhere. Thank you safe distancing ambassadors for keeping us safe while we play. #thankful
Most importantly, don‚Äôt forget to bring an extra set of clothes and MASK for both you and your kids! You don‚Äôt want to wear a sweat soak mask for 5hrs... #notsponsored #justsharing #thanksforreading #happymonday

So the hermits finally decided to head out and visit the Cloud Forest at Gardens by the Bay over the weekend üòã. We had visited the Cloud Forest when Big E was still a pre-schooler and I remember she was rather scared of the height and loud noise from the waterfall, and it also felt too cold for us then as we weren't dressed for it üòÖ. But this time round with the girls older and everyone dressed for it, the girls were able to better appreciate the environment and blooms. The mist, greens and light filtering in from the dome give the Cloud Forest such a magical quality that we all enjoyed the trip so much. 
.
If you're planning to visit too, do book your tickets early. We waited till the end of the week and by then most of the weekend slots were fully booked. But thanks to the limited capacity too, it wasn't crowded at all and we felt quite comfortable during our visit.
.
Btw you don't see many pics of us here, maybe it's just me but somehow with the masked faces, I find that the pics with us don't look so nice üòÖ Anyway, we were all happy to be out finally and are now thinking of where to go for the coming weekend so we can book ahead if necessary üòÜ Any suggestions? Meanwhile have a happy week ahead! üòò

A kampong's beauty
.
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singapore‚Äôs mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each other‚Äôs presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkok‚Äôs postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises. 
.

Exploring the hidden gems of Chinatown and Little India

üìçChinatown
‚Ä¢Sago Lane / Street of the Dead - In earlier times, funeral parlours lined up this lane.
‚Ä¢People's Park - the "people's shopping centre", the complex is strategically located in one of the most populous areas in Singapore's Central Business District. Also nicknamed as "Streets in the Air"
‚Ä¢Jinrikisha Station - last reminder of the once ubiquitous rickshaw (and yes, it used to be a rickshaw terminal)

üìçLittle India
‚Ä¢Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple - one of the oldest Hindu Temple in Singapore (Gopuram/ front tower in photo) 
‚Ä¢Flower Stalls - every street corner of Little India has this
‚Ä¢House of Tan Teng Niah - the last surviving Chinese Villa in Little India
‚Ä¢Sajeev Photography Studio - Most clients are foreign workers whose portaits are sent to their parents back home, to look for their potential brides. (see all those film rolls? can you imagine the numerous love stories that were developed from those!)

Rediscovering Singapore is like getting to know her again for the first time..this time, she looks lovelier than ever as she unfolds stories that were almost forgotten.
.

[Little India Precinct] - The Flower Guys of Little India

This is dedicated to the friendly and 
handsome flower garland selling guys of Little India.

Rediscovery is about relooking and presenting the beauty of people in their environment

I am always attracted to the stalls selling colorful flower garlands. Those flower garlands are used for religious purposes during those festivals. Often, those guys are so friendly and always open for a nice photo and chitchat. As I rediscover, I see the beautiful people ( those eyes.. ) and color flower. Cannot help but to capture them in my photos.

Yesterday. All was peaceful and calm in the beautiful Bambusetum. The sun shone through the wispy bamboo leaves, casting dappled patterns on the path, and a slight breeze made them rustle soothingly. And then suddenly, the silence was broken. Someone was belting out Mandarin songs at the top of his voice. It seemed to be coming from the small gazebo perched above me. But as he was so enjoying himself and putting so much soulful expression into his songs, it seemed only right to leave him to it. He sure did have a powerful set of lungs though for he continued at full strength for more than an hour as I moseyed about the Learning Forest...

.
.
.
.

Yay we finally went to the Artscience Museum! In the Future World:
Where Art Meets Science exhibition, there were lots of fun for us as we explored the interactive installations. Some of them were breathtaking and lots were simply very cute!!!! 

We highly recommend a visit there because it's just too fun! There's proper crowd control and you will be given a pair of gloves since there are lots of interactive screens. Sanitisers are available everywhere for the younger ones who can't keep their gloves on. 

Highlighting a few artworks

üÖ∞ üÜÉüÖ∞üÖ±üÖªüÖ¥ üÜÜüÖ∑üÖ¥üÜÅüÖ¥ üÖªüÖ∏üÜÉüÜÉüÖªüÖ¥ üÖøüÖ¥üÖæüÖøüÖªüÖ¥ üÖªüÖ∏üÜÖüÖ¥
The little people will jump onto your hand or object you place on the table. Check out the pan where you can cook an egg. üòÅ This is just cute to the max!

üÖªüÖ∏üÖ∂üÖ∑üÜÉ üÖ±üÖ∞üÖªüÖª üÖæüÜÅüÖ≤üÖ∑üÖ¥üÜÇüÜÉüÜÅüÖ∞
Push, bounce and roll the lighted balls to create your own orchestra! The kids couldn't stop running about to push the balls and watch them change colours. Too fun!

üÜÇüÖ∫üÖ¥üÜÉüÖ≤üÖ∑ üÜÉüÖæüÜÜüÖΩ
Watch your artwork ( buildings or vehicles) come to life on the big screen here. Just grab the paper and crayons provided and colour away. After scanning them, they appear on the screen and vehicles start to move around. It's amazing to see your creations come to life. 

Check out our IG TV for more! 

It was a well spent afternoon with family and we hope to go there and have another round of fun soon! üòÅ

15 TRENGGANU STREET history:
Located at corner of Temple Street, at junction with Trengganu Street.

After my shave, I chanced upon The Heritage shop. Home to a variety of antiques, I was really surprised they even carried the Canon 518 Super 8 movie camera (google it, it‚Äôs vintage!). Step inside and you‚Äôll be transported to 40 years ago, which was when owner Mr Patrick started amassing his collection. He respectfully declined a photograph of the shop‚Äôs interior as he charges for it. However, he welcomes all to visit his place. 

Crawford street was my final stop. Allegedly home to some of Singapore‚Äôs oldest shops, what drew my eye was Adi‚Äôs barber. What sets this barber apart is it‚Äôs high ceiling and television area. Owner Mr Adi left the shop untended for a bit, and then I realised how the residents really trusted one another enough to leave a shop open like Mr Adi. Beyond the long-established brick and mortar stalls, I sensed something that cannot be captured through photography alone - ‚Äúkampung spirit‚Äù, that sense of community and resilience that transcends time and continues to live on in these hidden spaces. 

Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. It‚Äôs an opportunity to re-live our nation‚Äôs history while tuning into modern narratives of ‚Äúhidden‚Äù spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

The new @apple Marina Bay Sands store, designed by @fosterandpartners, appears as a floating sphere entirely surrounded by Singapore's Marina Bay.‚Å†
‚Å†
Billed as the tech giant's most ambitious retail project, the store is self-supporting dome structure: 30 metres in diameter, 17 metres tall, made up of 114 glass panels lined interior baffles that provide shade while bouncing light upwards. Visitors enter via the store's lower floor, connected to the Marina Bay Sands shopping mall, and ascend a pair of escalators that travel through a stainless steel tunnel to enter the spectacular domed space. A Pantheon-style oculus at the top of the dome lets in a disc of light for added dramatic effect.

A few years back, from a small stall at a pop-up food village with his iconic Durian Creme Br√ªl√©e, that was my first encounter with Chef Deming. His love, passion and advocacy for local Singapore food can be seen, felt and tasted at The Quarters. Beyond and above, his forward-tasting and thinking in local Singapore cuisine started a new wave of modern Singapore (Mod-Sin) cuisine through a fusion of traditional and modern cuisine, in a communal dining known as The Quarters Experience. 

More than just preserving and holding on to our local Singapore food cuisine and culinary, Chef Deming belongs to a group of young food entrepreneurs leading the way to preserve, uphold and spread an important segment of our Singapore‚Äôs intangible cultural heritage and our love obsession with food. 

The time is now to start your own #SingapoRediscovers #sgfood journey! Visit @thequarterssg and rediscover a new world of Mod-Sin cuisine. 

#PortraitsofPurpose @dbsbank

Have you gotten it right? üòÜüòú

The answer is Leopard Corydoras, which is commonly known as Corydoras julii! Great job to those who guessed correctly! For the rest of us, nice try! Let‚Äôs all try harder again in the next round! 

Corydoras julii is not demanding and tolerates a range of initial water parameters. Water can be slightly acidic to slightly alkaline, with soft to medium-hard water hardness. The substrate in this fish‚Äôs tank must be soft, as it will scavenge the bottom for bits of food. Sand or small and smooth gravel is suitable. Driftwood is recommended, as well as other items that can serve as hiding places. Plants are also essential. Floating plants are often used to dim the lighting, as this fish does not appreciate bright lights.

Furthermore, Corydoras julii accepts most food. You can offer it sinking tablets or pellets as their primary diet. Live foods like brine shrimp, daphnia, and bloodworms can be offered to supplement their diet. Because it is a nocturnal, it is best to feed it before lights are turned off.

Lastly, Corydoras julii is best kept in a school of a minimum of four or more. It gets along well with small catfish and small peaceful fish. Possible tankmates include small members of the tetra family, rasboras, dwarf cichlids, danios and other small community fish. You should avoid any large or aggressive fish.

‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Lloyd's Inn Singapore: To all guests (past, present, future), thank you for your support. We are proud to say that during the last few months, trying as they may be, we neither cut wages nor let go of staff. This is because of the support from the local staycation market. In fact, we are hiring additional members to the team. 
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Every booking made supports consumption in the domestic tourism industry. Every staycation supports the livelihood of our team. Although business is not as optimal as pre-Covid times, we endeavour to preserve the staycation spirit for as best as we can. 
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
In our in-room guide, we have curated local experiences one can enjoy and explore. On social media, we will continue sharing our own travel experiences within Singapore via #lloydsinnexplores. 
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
We do encourage all locals to visit the attractions and experiences around Singapore. With the $100 #SingapoRediscovers incentive given by the government, spending it either on Staycations or exploring new sights, it is a cause we support for the local tourism industry. A little spending from each person goes a long way in supporting someone else's livelihood.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
We champion for an inclusive nation with mutual support and hope to offer other tourism businesses support as well. Thank you all for your support, and see you really soon at Lloyd's Inn or around Singapore! More on stories today on our team behind-the-scenes >>>

‚ÄúLittle India is filled with vibrant colours that represent its rich culture and heritage. Besides Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple on Serangoon Road, one of the oldest temples in Singapore that was built in 1881, you can also explore Shree Lakshminarayan Temple, Singapore‚Äôs first dedicated place of worship for Northern Indian Hindus. 
 
Some other buildings that caught my eye over the years are two historical churches ‚Äì Kampong Kapor Methodist Church and Church of the True Light. Not forgetting the Abdul Gafoor Mosque and the eclectic exterior of Sakya Muni Buddha Gaya Temple. All these buildings add unexpectedly to the vibrant facade of Little India.‚Äù
 
Captured by @darrensohphoto as part of #SingapoRediscovers.

Another photo stop along Coney Island Promenade. 

There were many other families sitting around and enjoying the view. The Promenade is good for families with strollers as beyond that, the paths are not as smooth. 

There were also some picnic-goers, but if you intend to bring food, do be warned that there are monkeys in Coney Island. As we walked on, we saw a group of them picking up plastic bottles and food packets left behind by other visitors. A reminder to all to do our part to maintain the natural state of the island and let‚Äôs not leave any rubbish behind.

Spring Well
‚ÄúVillage of Hot Water‚Äù
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

In 1909, a Chinese merchant named Seah Eng Keong, the son of Chinese pioneer Seah Liang Seah, discovered hot springs in his pineapple estate in Sembawang. The three springs were channelled into one, so that the water would be conveniently concentrated in one area. A well was built along with the spring, which became popular with the villagers, who frequently sought the waters for their supposed healing powers. The spring's fame spread, resulting in the village becoming known as Kampong Ayer Panas, which means "Village of Hot Water" in Malay.

Soft drinks firm Fraser & Neave (F&N) acquired the site in 1922, & set up a bottling plant at nearby Semangat Ayer to tap the mineral water, which they labelled Seletaris. During the Second World War, the spring's flow was temporarily interrupted when a bomb fell near the well during a Japanese air raid over Singapore in 1942. After the fall of Singapore, the Japanese military seized the place & converted it into recreational thermal baths (onsen).

The hot spring was frequented by gamblers in 1960, who took "good luck" baths before the start of horse races. That same year, the villagers urged the authorities to develop the area into a spa-like onsen tourist resort. However, F&N shelved the suggestion after geologists could not trace the source of the spring water. In 1967, the proposal of the spa surfaced again, when F&N proposed plans for the development of a bathhouse, restaurants, a miniature golf course & even a nature reserve. However, the plans did not materialize, so the hot spring remained untouched & forgotten.

Space for Interaction

Beyond the exterior fa√ßade of being a vibrant place for Singaporeans and tourists to visit, Kampong Gelam is first and foremost a community. Even today, while its early days residents have left, Kampong Gelam continues to instill its energy and vibrance into its visitors, connecting people.

Friends and family, young and old, may find a space in this community that they may relate. This, in particular, can be observed if one were to walk along Haji Lane where friends gather in bars and engage in merrymaking day and night, capturing and creating memories against the colourful shophouses. Not to forget, the relationships forged between the shophouse owners, employers and employees over time. Strangers arrive at Haji Lane and may leave as friends. It's a place to feel alive, to be alive!

post_caption:
Delightful chaos and beautiful disarray. That is usually the state of the studio after a full day of workshops.
.
TBH, preparing for and cleaning up after classes take up a lot of time and frankly aren't much fun at all. And these are just some of many invisible behind-the-scenes things we do to create the art experience we want to deliver for every single guest who visit the studio. 
.
But the hard work all pays off when we see the galore of works that our workshop participants create after every session. Each piece different and always inspiring in one way or another. And if even when only one person leaves the studio having a renewed perspective towards art, we do a little dance in our heart.üíÉ
.
So when you're feeling tired like we do today, take a moment to look for that delight in chaos and beauty in disarray, and then find new strength to keep going. For us, we wake up grateful every day to be able to call this our career, our passion and our mission üë©üèª‚Äçüé® Here's to another brand new day. Fighting!
.
#gratitudeüôè #artforthesoul #whywedowhatwedo

We finally explored a beautiful oasis so close to our home here in Singapore: the Sembawang Hot Springs. We rode our bikes and found great bike park facilities, restrooms and surprisingly a cafe that rents & sells buckets for the hot springs. The pools are nestled in regenerated natural bush and the only sign of the busy neighbourhood is the occasional helicopter overhead.  The surprise and delight of the ‚Äòegg cooking‚Äô station was surpassed by our genuine surprise at how hot the water is in the foot bath spring pool. We‚Äôll definitely be back (with a bucket).

Recovery Walk along East coast for Food & Coffee. Past by a few heritages establishments. Guillemard Camp (1969-2003) -  home to the First Singapore Infantry Regiment. One of the oldest furniture shops in Singapore, that specialises in classic rattan furniture. A old styled coffee and bakes that is permanently closed. A new Starbucks outlet at colonial-era former¬†Joo Chiat Police Station that was built in 1928. And lastly, Katong Shopping Centre - the first air-conditioned mall in Singapore. We took the kids to Mega Bounce @megaadventuresingapore @sentosa_island on Saturday. It was their first time trying bungee trampolines and turned out to be a pretty fun experience for them. Took a little getting used to initially but they were soon happily bouncing on the trampolines (can't do flips and turns yet though üòÜ).
.
The activity is only for 5 minutes ($15 usual price or ten tokens from the Sentosa fun pass), so we bought for 10 minutes each with our Sentosa fun passes. It really just cost us $10 each child as we bought the Mastercard 1-for-1 fun pass promo which gives us 2 fun passes with 60 tokens each at $60.
.
Turned out ten minutes were just enough for them as it was pretty hot (you can jump with your nose uncovered under your mask but my girls were OK covered up) and they said their harnesses were starting to feel a lil uncomfortable near the end. But they would definitely like to return for it another time!
.
We were all pretty beat by the end of the day because of the hot weather üòÖ How was your weekend? üòä

„ÄêAng Mo Kio #3 - Fried Rice„Äë
Did you know that it was in the 1970s, that the Chinese name for Ang Mo Kio was changed to ‚ÄúÂÆèËåÇÊ°•‚Äú which means "Bridge of Expansiveness and Prosperity‚Äù? Surely such an auspicious name bodes well for the hawkers in this neighbourhood!

China has the earliest record for fried rice from 1,500 years ago. Fried rice is believed to have originated from the Chinese practice of creating a meal with the leftover dishes (and rice) from the  previous meal. Our tradition of not wasting food created a whole new genre of Chinese cuisine.  Some of the usual ingredients for fried rice are rice, scallion, eggs and other small bits of meats & vegetables. 

In Singapore, we have the Chinese version which comes with side dishes like fried egg, hot dog sausage, pork cutlet, etc. Nasi Goreng is the Malay version of fried rice, usually  stir-fried with ikan bilis (anchovies) and tomato sauce. Perhaps because of all the different types of fried rice we get to taste in Singapore, we are known as the ‚ÄòFried Rice Paradise‚Äô ?

What kind of ingredients do you  include in your fried rice? Comment below and share with us. See you on Thursday and see where we dabao this delicious packet of fried rice full of ‚Äòwok hei‚Äô. See ya!

The good old days at Tee Seng Store. Putting everything together, hope u like it...

Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise¬†qigong¬†before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung¬†spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...

I‚Äôve been to South Beach couple of times in the past but only for dining. This time round after a night of exploration, I realized there is so much history and innovation behind the place - it really is an attraction on its own!

We chanced upon this corner and love how it captures the blend of heritage with modern architecture - the new building set against the old SAF NCO Club and the arched entrance of the old block 9. 

Singapore has been progressing at such a fast pace with our landscape always  changing with new developments, so all the more I appreciate the restoration work by South Beach to keep a part of our history alive. 

Hope by sharing what I see though my amateur eyes, you may be inspired to rediscover Singapore too „Ä∞Ô∏è

Guess the fish! üê†üêü

Indigenous to the lower Amazon region, primarily the Parna√≠ba River of Brazil, this mystery fish is found in flooded forest regions as well as in creeks and small tributaries. This fish typically is smaller and more stout in build. It has a shorter head and rounded snout. Also, it has a silvery gray body. Furthermore, a dark zigzag stripe runs along the lateral line from its gill to its tail. Above and below this dark line is a section that is not spotted, beyond which are many small, isolated black spots of varying size. 

Additionally, its dorsal fin is transparent with a large black blotch on the upper fin that does not extend down into the body. The caudal fin has vertical rows of dark brown spots that gives the appearance of striping. The anal, adipose, pectoral, and ventral fin also has these spots, but it is much paler in colour than on the caudal fin. Instead of scales, this fish has overlapping hard plates, known as scutes.
Overall, this fish can reach an adult size of slightly over 2 inches.

Stay tuned as the answer will be revealed tomorrow!

What makes the Mid-Autumn Festival special for you and your family? Is it the family gatherings, savouring of mooncakes, or making your own lanterns?

 To take part, simply: 
1. Follow our Instagram (@chinatown_festivals) and like this post
2. Share with us your most creative photo showing how you and your family enjoy the Mid-Autumn Festival with a short caption on what you love about the festival

The 27 metres long kiln is fired up with wood, creating rivers of fire that engulf the pots in it. The melting ashes then deposit themselves on the pots and reacts with their glazes. This process results in precious one-of-a-kind wares, where each has unique flushes of scorch marks depending of its position in the kiln.

At Thow Kwang, the dragon kiln is fired two to three times a year.
