Warehouse
.
.
.
.

The Warehouse Hotel was built in 1895 along the Singapore River as part of the Straits of Malacca trade route. At that time, the area was a hotbed of secret societies, underground activity, and liquor distilleries. Today, while much of that history has disappeared, The Warehouse Hotel has been meticulously restored as a modern 37-room boutique hotel, focusing on heritage and local culture.

Singapore Tourism Board (@stb_sg) and Visa have signed a three-year MoU to buoy up tourism and lifestyle SMEs that have been impacted by Covid-19. The collaboration focuses on two areas to revive the local tourism industry: marketing partnerships, as well as joint research and analytics.

In the first phase of their marketing partnership, which will be launched in October 2020, both organisations will tap on their respective campaigns ‚Äì #SingapoRediscovers and #WhereYouShopMatters ‚Äì to encourage Singaporeans to shop from local retailers and support the domestic economy.

A Living Space

Strolling along the streets of Kampong Gelam, one may find many shophouses providing all sorts of services such as hairstyling, food and drinks and souvenirs; there are also shophouses selling colourful Turkish lamps, mats, or aromatic perfumes and fragrances. What caught my eye on this particular trip, however, were the Turkish lamps that offered a dazzling array of colours -- it fitted perfectly in this district of vibrant walls and colourful shophouses.

For the employers and employees of the various shophouses, Kampong Gelam is not just a place for recreation. It's also a place of livelihood. It's a place where they spend most of their waking hours living. As seen here, this at times includes temporarily transforming these public spaces into their personal living space -- a space for prayer. It's a space to feel alive and to be alive.

The topic of reading today is on ‚ÄúSucceeding in Singapore & Japan‚Äù.

As a consulting expert in retail, Japan and entrepreneurship, we have to constantly reading up to gain new knowledge, analyse the current markets, and devise new strategies, short, mid and long term to stay ahead of the curve. 

The current headwinds in the industry, uncertainties worldwide and perfect storm tensions in north asia, we are caught in the storm of the lifetime. 

Yet, we must never take our eyes off the vision, we must keep moving towards it. Taking steps to work out the right direction, hiring the right people to power the efforts, and reaching out to the targeted markets.

The lease in Mandarin Gallery is due for renewal this October. We hope the terms will be workable and the Reits is appreciating the long term efforts we have put in. And all our customers too.

Tee Seng Store is one of Singapore‚Äôs oldest provision stores. Located in a quiet private housing estate, this modest shop has been operated by Mr Ang Lu Heng since 1955.
.
Provision shops ‚Äì known colloquially as mini-marts, mama shops, or zhap hueh diam (ÊùÇË¥ßÂ∫ó) ‚Äì are witnesses to our memories, both personal and shared. Many of us often take these provision shops for granted, only remembering how important they are when we need an ice-cold drink, the occasional bottle of soya sauce, or that essential packet of coconut milk for our curries.
.
Many of us also grew up with the uncles and aunties who ran the provision shops ‚Äì just like Mr Ang here. The octogenarian wakes up at 5am daily to practice qigong before opening his store at 8am like clockwork. Over the years, Mr Ang has built up a small but loyal following of customers, whose names and orders he knows by heart. This is the familiarity that modern supermarket chains and convenience stores cannot give. Because what the humble provision shop lacks in newfangled products, it more than makes up for in faithfulness and a wealth of memories.
.
Stepping into Tee Seng Store was like taking a trip down memory lane. Mr Ang once used a Milkmaid tin that dangled from the ceiling to store cash. Now, he uses a cash register. I was fortunate to have Mr Ang‚Äôs permission to take pictures of his store while he worked. These pictures are precious reminders of days gone by.
.
Rediscovering Singapore does not have to be anything grand. To me, it is about revisiting these living artefacts of Singapore‚Äôs past and getting reacquainted with these simple but deeply cherished memories of growing up.
.

A different experience exploring in the dark and coming up close to animals at night. You can only do this at the Night Safari, the world's first nocturnal zoo! It was the kids' first time at the Night Safari and we had a great time there! There were moments where it was pitch dark when we were on the tram and our senses were heightened so we could spot, hear or smell something nearby. 

Swipe to check out our video where we had close encounters with hyenas and cheetahs! 

The kids were exhausted after we exited the Night Safari because it was close to their bedtime but they agreed that it was an awesome and refreshing experience to see animals at night. We missed the Creatures of the Night Show because it was full but we will be back again!

Shopping for Natural Spring Water
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

During its peak, up to 300 people visited the hot spring daily. On 1 March 2002, it was closed for two months while upgrading & improvement works were carried out to the area around the spring, which had become sodden & muddy. Littering had also become a problem because of the increased numbers of visitors. The former dirt track leading to the spring was paved with cement, & lined with bougainvillea bushes & high fences to ensure the security of the air base. Drainage pipes were also installed. Mindef, which owns the land, allows public access between 7 am and 7 pm daily, free-of-charge. When the spring reopened on 1 May 2002, more than 100 people visited the site despite the afternoon drizzle. At the same time, some new free-hold condominiums were built in the surrounding area; one of the developments, built by the property arm of F&N in 2001, is called Seletaris, named after the company's former mineral water.

In July 2005, a Business Times reader proposed that the authorities should explore the possibility of tapping the geothermal heat that lies many miles under Sembawang‚Äîsimilar to the project in South Australia's Cooper Basin‚Äîin order to aid Singapore's reliance on oil and gas. The proposal was not acted upon.

 As of 2014, the well can still be seen locked inside a red-brick enclosure with a steel gate, & its geothermal heat can be felt outside the building. Some plastic chairs, pails and mini-tubs kindly donated by visitors are stored at the perimeter of the compound, which has a makeshift shed in one corner. A caretaker, paid for by Mindef, takes care of the place to maintain its overall cleanliness, but there is no toilet on location. The hot spring is less frequented nowadays but remains rustic for rural & suburban families to discover & explore.

Not many would expect to find a small, quiet village tucked away in the modern metropolis that is Singapore. Yet here stands Kampong Lorong Buangkok: Singapore‚Äôs ùóπùóÆùòÄùòÅ ùó∏ùóÆùó∫ùóΩùóºùóªùó¥ and a relic of a simpler and slower way of life.
.
In the minds of younger Singaporeans today, the kampong is a construct of oral history passed down from their parents and grandparents. Few have seen an actual kampong in the flesh. Far from being secluded, Kampong Lorong Buangkok is but a few metres away from the residential area of Yio Chu Kang. The zinc and wood houses of this little village stand in stark contrast to the concrete of its neighbouring HDB flats.
.
Kampong Lorong Buangkok is a rare gem: it is a part of Singapore‚Äôs living history, one which might soon be lost to the unceasing pace of development and renewal in this city-state. To say that I felt an overwhelming sense of nostalgia would have been excessively romantic. Like many of my millennial peers I grew up not knowing what kampong living was like. Visiting this little kampong is not simply akin to traveling back in time and gaining a glimpse of the kampong experience. It is about rediscovering Singapore ‚Äì the Singapore once inhabited by my grandparents. To be able to see how they might have once lived is truly a blessing: in rediscovering Singapore, I have also gained a deeper appreciation of my own roots.
.

A Love Story

Rediscovering Singapore has once again led me to a place I didn't know existed. This time, it brought me to the house of Tan Teng Niah. Little India is not short of colourful shophouses -- not unlike Kampong Gelam -- but the house of Tan Teng Niah stood out for me first and foremost with the Chinese engraving on its front door. "A Chinese residence in Little India?" That was the thought that first surfaced to my mind. In fact, I chanced upon this place, attracted by the colours and the inscription.

Written on the front door of this vividly vibrant house is a couplet referring to the wife of Tan Teng Niah, ÁßÄÊùæ. While I did not manage to find any sources on an interpretation of the couplet, from my very basic Chinese understanding (hopefully not embarrassing my Chinese teachers), the couplet describes her wife as a beautiful (ÁßÄ‰∏ΩÊôØËâ≤), pure and morally upright person (ÊùæÊüèÊìçÊåÅ). While one can only guess why he made such a couplet, we may infer that Tan Teng Niah left the couplet on the door for the generations to come, to remember not just him but also his wife. He sounds like a romantic, loving husband if you were to ask me.

I make both snowskin mooncakes and traditional  mooncakes (with different favours and designs) with my family every Mid Autumn Festival. May the brightness of the moon and the stars fill our lives with positivity and happiness.  Sending best wishes on auspicious occasion of Mid Autumn Festival.

Little India is filled with vibrant colours that represent its rich culture and heritage. Besides Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple on Serangoon Road, one of the oldest temples in Singapore that was built in 1881, you can also explore Shree Lakshminarayan Temple, Singapore‚Äôs first dedicated place of worship for Northern Indian Hindus.
¬†
Some other buildings that caught my eye over the years are two historical churches ‚Äì Kampong Kapor Methodist Church and Church of the True Light. Not forgetting the Abdul Gafoor Mosque and the eclectic exterior of Sakya Muni Buddha Gaya Temple. All these buildings add unexpectedly to the vibrant facade of Little India.
¬†
Take a look at all the spots I have rediscovered over at @STB_SG, and share your own pictures with #SingapoRediscovers.
¬†

House of Tan Teng Niah

This vividly colorful house is located at Little India and was constructed in 1900 by a local businessman named Tan Teng Niah. It underwent a full restoration during the 1980s to what people see today. This vibrant and beautiful building has stood the test of time, representing hope and resilience. 

Conservational buildings, like the House of Tan Teng Niah, are being preserved to keep a balance between the modern and traditional structures. These buildings are valued because of their history and their significant impact to which I believe more people, not only locals but tourists too, should rediscover and learn more about. The intrinsic and unique design of these buildings will surely captivate your eyes.

Old and New meet at the ever changing, glam Kampong Glam.

Pigeons famous, Kampong Glam is the Muslim center of Singapore, and is traditionally home to mosques, carpet shops, and Middle Eastern cuisine, while more recently the area has seen a surge in boutique cocktail bars and funky restaurant openings. Sightseers will enjoy the picturesque streets with their beautifully restored shophouses, while shoppers are in for a treat with a selection of Singapore‚Äôs best offbeat boutiques selling cult labels and vintage clothing.

(Oh yes, after only 200 shots her majesty the glam pigeon quickly flew into place which is appreciated by me.)

[Chinatown Precinct] - ‚ÄúPotato Head‚Äù

Rediscovering is about appreciate the historic value of a place and the finding the best time to shoot it. 

When rediscovering Chinatown, the pre-war shophouses at the junction of Keong Saik Road and Teck Lim Road ( dated 1939) should not be missed.¬† This place has a colorful and rowdy past until 1980. It¬† is now occupied by the restaurant-bar Potato Head and now nicknamed as Potato Head. I love the heritage chic and vibe of this area at night. As a photographer, I find it most beautiful in the bluehour of the early morning. This photo was taken during blue hour and just before a heavy rain( which explains the lens flare from the rain drops)

*Taken during the stipulated period. It is challenging during a rainy period. Hope that I made  best of situation.

Looking for hidden photography spots in Singapore, while hoping to win attractive prizes at the same time? We‚Äôve got you covered! Together with the Singapore Tourism Board, we‚Äôve worked with @aikbengchia to put together an itinerary of 10 spots across 6 local precincts for you. Check out our LINK IN BIO to download the full itinerary to begin exploring these ‚ÄúHidden Gems!‚Äù

You don‚Äôt have to limit yourselves to these locations though - any "hidden spots" within the 6 precincts are welcome.
¬†
From now until 4 October, you can submit your photo entries for the contest. To do so, visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured and share at least 2x original shots captured in your own style (we‚Äôve included example photo spots in the itinerary, but your photos can be captured at other spots as well). These can be carousel-style posts or separate posts ‚Äì the more the better! 
¬†
Do also ensure that you:
1.¬†Follow both @stb_sg and @sg_photocommunity on Instagram.
2. Tag both accounts in your post and include the hashtags #SPCRediscovers and #SingapoRediscovers.
3.¬†In the post caption, share what rediscovering Singapore means to you.
¬†
Winners will be chosen based on the most creative visual along with the best accompanying caption.
¬†
If your shots are chosen, you have a chance to win the following attractive prizes:
¬†
-1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
-2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)

Went down to take photos of this grand structure designed by @fosterandpartners over the course of 2 weeks (ok not all 14 days) and also had to book a "appointment" to see the interior - wasn't disappointed at all.

The first ever Apple store to have an escalator, as well as the first to be floating on water - it truly is a sight to behold, especially at night, when it forms part of the Singapore skyline.

There is truly more to see around this tiny red dot than what most people will perceive, so take time, explore the neighborhoods, hike trails, eat at places where you normally won't venture to - and maybe you might just be rewarded with something unexpectedly good.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] Beyond the colorful

Rediscovery is about having a listening ear and appreciation to the heritage of the place.

Joo Chiat is a place with so much rich history as well as street ‚Äúhistorians‚Äù. In both visits, I have had strangers who are residents or former residents coming to chit chat with me. They told me interesting stories as well as places to shoot. Most of us, including myself, will focus a lot of attention on the colorful peranakan house.¬† One of them ( her name is Diana)¬† was told that there are more. For example, I should also be paying attention to the tiles of those other chinese or penakan houses. Those are imported from Europe in the pre-war days, and often use a symbol of wealth for people staying in the area.¬†

She also shared something interesting about what is shown in the last photo. Can you guess what that is for?

Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

Went back to Jewel again this weekend and visited Canopy Bridge (not part of Canopy Park btw)! The bridge gives you a close up view of the Jewel waterfall five stories up! Other than the close-up and height, the novelty of the bridge also lies in the fact that it is translucent (I say translucent as I couldn't see thru clearly due to reflection) so my younger girl was a bit scared üòÖ Oh, and we really like the effect of the mist when we enter the bridge üòÑ
.
Actually I had thought  the bridge would let us walk around the waterfall but you only get to walk past the waterfall and it's really quite a short bridge. If you don't linger to take photos, you'll be at the other end within a minute üòÇ
.
Tickets cost us $3.60 each. Guess I didn't really mind as I bought the tics with the 55% discount they are having for Jewel attractions (only till 31 August). I probably wouldn't pay full price for this üòÖ But still, we had a good ten minute fun enjoying the view and having wobbly knees üòÑ How did your weekend go? üòâ

Mention Singapore and most people would immediately associate it with skyscrapers and high-rise flats, But what if we told you that you can still find a kampong (village) beyond the bustling city? As a West-sider, the Eastern part of Singapore is somewhere I rarely step foot into. A month back, while visiting a friend in the east, I decided to explore Joo Chiat/Katong area - Singapore‚Äôs first Heritage Town. 

Since then, I‚Äôve returned twice more to check off a handful of must-eats there, and to hunt down Instagrammable spots like these unique pre-war shophouses.

Moments like this make me think about the upside of being trapped in Singapore (although not indefinitely). I‚Äôm ‚Äúforced‚Äù to rediscover my country, which brings along opportunities to learn about and view this little red dot through a different lens. Can‚Äôt wait to check out more sights & makan places around Singapore , and looking forward to playing host to foreign friends again when leisure travel resumes!

Instructor: Tony Sugiarta‚Å£

This workshop is part of 1+1 = Infinity: A Collaborative Digital Batik Art (www.batikinfinity.com) project by @anerdgallery, in collaboration with Lokka Lekkr Makers Studio. The project is part of #SGCultureAnywhere and is supported by National Arts Council.‚Å£
‚Å£
Batik is both personal and collaborative. Batik is both structured and free. Batik is both wild and meditative. Let's explore Batik!‚Å£
‚Å£
Let's create a batik artwork/pattern that reflects your "Singapore". In this two-hour session, we will introduce common batik motifs as a warm-up and as an inspiration. This will be followed by a guided batik-making session where you will explore your inner artistic expression while tapping on the creative exchange among your fellow artists. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Need technical help about batik-making for the project? Or you simply want to have fun creating artworks with friends? Join us in this unique in-person session, get inspired and express yourself in batik!‚Å£
‚Å£
Note: This session is designed for adult participants. However, the DIY batik kit is suitable for participants who are 7 years old and above. You may sign-up to get it delivered to your place at batikinfinity.com/register. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Tony Sugiarta is the founder of aNERDgallery, "an-art-gallery" which specialises in promoting Indonesian textile art of batik and tenun. Through the platform, Tony aims to educate and to connect makers and textile enthusiasts through experiential workshops, exhibitions and textile trips.‚Å£

<341> ‚ÄúRunning From A Hill To Another‚Äù

Can you imagine running from a hill to another via a bridge? 

As a young boy who grew up in Telok Blangah, I always had to chose between Mount Faber or Telok Blangah Hill for hiking. It‚Äôs too much a hassle to go up and down two hills at one go. 

The two neighbouring hills, which were then separated by a road, is now connected by a stylish wave-shaped bridge. The bridge‚Äôs shape creates shell-like sheltered spaces where visitors can rest and enjoy the scenery. But these resting areas have been closed by the authorities to avoid gathering of crowds.

Since there is no place to take a breather, I ran across the beautiful bridge as fast as I could like the man in front of me! 

William

My father would tell some old Chinese folktales, I should have written them all, can‚Äôt remember many now. Wish could do that with my kids but... err... that would mean the HDB corridor? üòÖ

Anyway today was a fun day out at #ChinatownSG after mostly playing at home. It was also so good that we didn‚Äôt really have crowd of tourists, and hence we spent the afternoon fooling around. Indeed it was a good idea to have a little #SingapoRediscovers time at Chinatown today. I guess this is how we enjoyed this year‚Äôs#ChinatownMAF2020, a bit different from past years but still we had a lot of fun... and food, yeah.  That was a big Yum Cha, I‚Äôm still full until now!

A must visit place says Ballo  either early in morning or evening ( before sunset) with your friends and family .

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
@ Leong Nam Temple 
ÈæçÂçóÊÆø‰πùÁöáÂ§ß‰∫åÂ∏ùÁà∑Âú£ËØû 
Rain or shine...devotees come in drove to offer prayers to the Nine Emperor Gods.
The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. Today, the younger generations have taken an interest in the festival, with many youths taking part in the processions. Involving the younger generations allows us to continue this intangible cultural heritage for many generations to come.

[Chinatown Precinct] - Past to present

Rediscovery is about looking for way to present a story. In this case, a story of past to present.

In the centre and background of the photo, it is the iconic public housing - Duxton that is built right in the heart of tanjong pagar. In the background, it is the¬† iconic ‚Äúpotato head‚Äù¬† pre-war shophouses with its beautiful and chic 5 foot walkway. This photo reminds us of Singapore‚Äôs progress from past to present. We should look forward to the near future when the pandemic is over and life goes back to normal again. Hope more people can continue to visit Singapore.

Like many Singaporeans, I‚Äôm a great fan of Mustafa Centre. This place started its journey as a makeshift shop set up by Mohamed Mustafa and his son to sell ready-made garments on Campbell Lane. Over the years, Mustafa Centre was gradually built up from one shop to two large buildings along Syed Alwi Road. It was only in 2003 that Mustafa Centre became a 24-hour shopping centre, now with some adjustments to its operating hours. Not to worry ‚Äì you can still buy almost anything there!
¬†
Take a look at all the spots I have rediscovered over at @STB_SG, and share your favourite part of Mustafa Centre with #SingapoRediscovers.

Let‚Äôs #Singapoliday and #singaporediscovers interesting places to visit with your family!!

We highly encourage a staycation at Government approved hotel. Staycation had been one of our TOP 1 favourite. Of all the 3 times we visited over these 6months, we seen improvement over improvement on the health protocol, great to know that the government agency and hotel are keeping our family safe. For this time, our choice of hotel had to be the one with swimming pool and waterplay for sure. It helps to keep adult and children occupied.

Shangri-La Hotel tick all the boxes for us. With the Playcation package we get to have alacarte breakfast at The Line, picnic basket, 100 bucks f&b credit per night, as well as freepass for The Buds indoor playground and The Splash Zone.

There‚Äôs many more activities for kids to do there!! (View last slide for the sample of activity that we had and the kiddo carepack).

Look at the kids smiling and laughing happily, we are glad that we ReDiscoverSingapore again. 

What should we do next??

Bukit Brown Cemetery

Estimated to house 100,000 tombs in a vast land size of about 0.86 square kilometers, Bukit Brown Cemetery has been abandoned since its closure in 1973. It was opened in 1922 by the Municipal Council (Municipal Council oversaw the supplies of water, electricity, gas, maintenance of roads, lighting and other administrative things in Singapore before 1965).

The grandest and largest tomb site in Bukit Brown Cemetery lies on its tallest hill and covers an area of  600 square meters, roughly the size of ten, 3- bedroom HDB flats (public housing apartments). 

Read Here For More Information : https://remembersingapore.org/bukit-brown-cemetery/
